{"title_page": "Jessica Marie Garcia", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jessica Marie Garcia\n| birth_name         = Jessica Marie Garcia\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|3|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Orlando, Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2010\u2013present\n| television         = ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' <br> ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' <br> ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''5 shes prettyyyyyy\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Adam Celorier|2018}}\n}}\n'''Jessica Marie Garcia''' (born March 23, 1987) is an American actress. She is known for her roles as [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow|Willow Cruz]] on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' and Jasmine Flores on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGarcia was born on March 23, 1987, in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref name=\"Life\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/tv-film/features/jessica-marie-garcia/|title=Jessica Marie Garcia: 11 facts about the On My Block star you probably didn\u2019t know|work=[[PopBuzz]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Garcia's father is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] descent, while her mother is of [[Cubans|Cuban]] descent.<ref name=\"Life\" /> At the age of 19, Garcia moved to [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Life\" /> Before pursuing acting, she worked at [[Olive Garden]] and a restaurant called The Counter, a job she continued while appearing on ''[[Liv and Maddie]]''.<ref name=\"OM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/jessica-marie-garcia/|title=10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know about Jessica Marie Garcia|work=[[TV Overmind]]|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In 2013, Garcia discovered that she was [[Prediabetes|pre-diabetic]], and to prevent getting diabetes, she lost over 70 pounds, stating that her career was her \"biggest motivation to start living a healthier life.\"<ref name=\"OM\" />\n\n==Career==\nGarcia made her professional acting debut on the [[ABC Family]] series ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]'' as Sierra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.galomagazine.com/movies-tv/jessica-marie-garcia-talks-abc-familys-huge-self-worth-and-choosing-to-be-healthy/|title=Jessica Marie Garcia Talks ABC Family's 'Huge,' Self-Worth And Choosing To Be Healthy|work=Galo|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Then from 2012 to 2014, she appeared in the ABC sitcom ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' as Becky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insouthmagazine.com/2019/03/14/cuban-actress-jessica-marie-garcia-stars-block/|title=Cuban actress Jessica Marie Garc\u00eda stars \"On my block\"|work=In South|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> During her appearances on ''The Middle'', Garcia began appearing on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' as [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow Cruz|Willow Cruz]], a role she portrayed until 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/liv-and-maddies-jessica-marie/amp|title=Liv and Maddie Star Jessica Marie Garcia on Losing Weight, Gaining Confidence, and Everything in Between|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> From 2015 to 2019, Garcia starred and co-wrote episodes in the comedy sketch show ''Betch''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deadline.com/2018/10/on-my-block-jessica-marie-garcia-jasmine-series-regular-netflix-1202474741/|title='On My Block': Jessica Marie Garcia Upped To Regular On Netflix Series|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Garcia began appearing in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]'' as Jasmine Flores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/03/on-my-block-netflix-review.html|title=On My Block Is a Remarkable Coming-of-Age Story|work=[[Vulture.com]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Originally cast in a recurring capacity, Garcia was promoted to a series regular from the second season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/amp/2020/03/on-my-block-season-3-jasmine.html|title=How On My Block Turned Jasmine From a Punch Line Into a Star|work=[[Vulture.com]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> For her portrayal of Jasmine, she was nominated for Choice Summer TV Actress at the [[2019 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8527134/teen-choice-awards-2019-winners-list|title=Teen Choice Awards: Full List of Winners|magazine=Billboard|date=August 11, 2019|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In 2020, she appeared in the [[Disney+]] series ''[[Diary of a Future President]]'' as Camila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/features/film/interview-jessica-maria-garcia-omb/|title='On My Block's Jessica Marie Garcia Loves Supporting Latino Shows: \"We Have to Raise Each Other Up\"|work=Remezcla|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2016, Garcia became engaged to actor Adam Celorier.<ref name=\"Wedding\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.j-14.com/posts/jessica-marie-garcia-married/|title='Liv and Maddie' Star Jessica Marie Garcia Is Married|work=[[J-14]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She married Celorier in October 2018.<ref name=\"Wedding\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]''\n| Sierra\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Las Angeles''\n| Lucero\n| Film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''County''\n| Vicky Santos\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]''\n| Becky\n| Recurring role; 11 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\u20132017\n| ''[[Liv and Maddie]]''\n| [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow|Willow Cruz]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n| 2015\u20132019\n| ''Betch''\n| Various\n| Also co-writer\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Casual (TV series)|Casual]]''\n| Marta\n| Episode: \"Phase 3\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Avenge the Crows''\n| Peaches\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''Hacking High School''\n| Becca\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''\n| Jasmine Flores\n| Recurring (season 1); main role (season 2\u2013)\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Goliath (TV series)|Goliath]]''\n| Ana\n| Episode: \"Alo\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Starter Pack''\n| Penley\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''\n| [[List of How to Get Away with Murder characters#Rhonda Navarro|Rhonda Navarro]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[American Princess (2019 TV series)|American Princess]]''\n| Nurse Paloma\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Filth''\n| Kevin\n| Episode: \"Filthy Bro Day\"\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Diary of a Future President]]''\n| Camilla\n| Recurring role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0305268}}\n* {{Twitter|JessMarieGarcia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garcia, Jessica Marie}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jessica Marie Garcia\n| birth_name         = Jessica Marie Garcia\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|3|23}}\n| birth_place        = [[Orlando, Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2010\u2013present\n| television         = ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' <br> ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' <br> ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Adam Celorier|2018}}\n}}\n'''Jessica Marie Garcia''' (born March 23, 1987) is an American actress. She is known for her roles as [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow|Willow Cruz]] on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' and Jasmine Flores on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGarcia was born on March 23, 1987, in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref name=\"Life\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.popbuzz.com/tv-film/features/jessica-marie-garcia/|title=Jessica Marie Garcia: 11 facts about the On My Block star you probably didn\u2019t know|work=[[PopBuzz]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Garcia's father is of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] descent, while her mother is of [[Cubans|Cuban]] descent.<ref name=\"Life\" /> At the age of 19, Garcia moved to [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Life\" /> Before pursuing acting, she worked at [[Olive Garden]] and a restaurant called The Counter, a job she continued while appearing on ''[[Liv and Maddie]]''.<ref name=\"OM\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/jessica-marie-garcia/|title=10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know about Jessica Marie Garcia|work=[[TV Overmind]]|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In 2013, Garcia discovered that she was [[Prediabetes|pre-diabetic]], and to prevent getting diabetes, she lost over 70 pounds, stating that her career was her \"biggest motivation to start living a healthier life.\"<ref name=\"OM\" />\n\n==Career==\nGarcia made her professional acting debut on the [[ABC Family]] series ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]'' as Sierra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.galomagazine.com/movies-tv/jessica-marie-garcia-talks-abc-familys-huge-self-worth-and-choosing-to-be-healthy/|title=Jessica Marie Garcia Talks ABC Family's 'Huge,' Self-Worth And Choosing To Be Healthy|work=Galo|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Then from 2012 to 2014, she appeared in the ABC sitcom ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' as Becky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insouthmagazine.com/2019/03/14/cuban-actress-jessica-marie-garcia-stars-block/|title=Cuban actress Jessica Marie Garc\u00eda stars \"On my block\"|work=In South|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> During her appearances on ''The Middle'', Garcia began appearing on the [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' as [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow Cruz|Willow Cruz]], a role she portrayed until 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/liv-and-maddies-jessica-marie/amp|title=Liv and Maddie Star Jessica Marie Garcia on Losing Weight, Gaining Confidence, and Everything in Between|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> From 2015 to 2019, Garcia starred and co-wrote episodes in the comedy sketch show ''Betch''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deadline.com/2018/10/on-my-block-jessica-marie-garcia-jasmine-series-regular-netflix-1202474741/|title='On My Block': Jessica Marie Garcia Upped To Regular On Netflix Series|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Garcia began appearing in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]'' as Jasmine Flores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/03/on-my-block-netflix-review.html|title=On My Block Is a Remarkable Coming-of-Age Story|work=[[Vulture.com]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Originally cast in a recurring capacity, Garcia was promoted to a series regular from the second season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/amp/2020/03/on-my-block-season-3-jasmine.html|title=How On My Block Turned Jasmine From a Punch Line Into a Star|work=[[Vulture.com]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> For her portrayal of Jasmine, she was nominated for Choice Summer TV Actress at the [[2019 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8527134/teen-choice-awards-2019-winners-list|title=Teen Choice Awards: Full List of Winners|magazine=Billboard|date=August 11, 2019|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In 2020, she appeared in the [[Disney+]] series ''[[Diary of a Future President]]'' as Camila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/features/film/interview-jessica-maria-garcia-omb/|title='On My Block's Jessica Marie Garcia Loves Supporting Latino Shows: \"We Have to Raise Each Other Up\"|work=Remezcla|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2016, Garcia became engaged to actor Adam Celorier.<ref name=\"Wedding\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.j-14.com/posts/jessica-marie-garcia-married/|title='Liv and Maddie' Star Jessica Marie Garcia Is Married|work=[[J-14]]|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She married Celorier in October 2018.<ref name=\"Wedding\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]]''\n| Sierra\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Las Angeles''\n| Lucero\n| Film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''County''\n| Vicky Santos\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]''\n| Becky\n| Recurring role; 11 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\u20132017\n| ''[[Liv and Maddie]]''\n| [[List of Liv and Maddie characters#Willow|Willow Cruz]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n| 2015\u20132019\n| ''Betch''\n| Various\n| Also co-writer\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Casual (TV series)|Casual]]''\n| Marta\n| Episode: \"Phase 3\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Avenge the Crows''\n| Peaches\n| Film\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''Hacking High School''\n| Becca\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u2013present\n| ''[[On My Block (TV series)|On My Block]]''\n| Jasmine Flores\n| Recurring (season 1); main role (season 2\u2013)\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Goliath (TV series)|Goliath]]''\n| Ana\n| Episode: \"Alo\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Starter Pack''\n| Penley\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[How to Get Away with Murder]]''\n| [[List of How to Get Away with Murder characters#Rhonda Navarro|Rhonda Navarro]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[American Princess (2019 TV series)|American Princess]]''\n| Nurse Paloma\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Filth''\n| Kevin\n| Episode: \"Filthy Bro Day\"\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Diary of a Future President]]''\n| Camilla\n| Recurring role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0305268}}\n* {{Twitter|JessMarieGarcia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garcia, Jessica Marie}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2601:204:c300:4ac0:797d:103c:bfb1:f25a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Marie_Garcia"}
{"title_page": "Quaternary sector of the economy", "text_new": "{{Tone|reason=passive voice and bland abstraction, as previously flagged by other editors|date=January 2019}}\n{{Economic sectors}}\n\nThe '''quaternary sector''' is the label used to describe a [[Knowledge economy|knowledge-based]]<ref name=twsJun17c>{{cite news\n |author = Tor Selstad\n |title= The rise of the quaternary sector. The regional dimension of wisdom or knowledge-based services in Norway, 1970\u20131985 - Norsk Geografisk Tidsskrift - Norwegian Journal of Geography - Volume 44, Issue 1\n |publisher= informaworld\n |quote= ... knowledge-based services ...\n |year= 1990\n |url= http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a792213401~tab=citations\n |accessdate= 2010-06-17\n}}</ref> [[economic sector|part]] of the economy, which typically includes knowledge-oriented economic sectors such as [[information technology]], [[mass media|media]], [[research and development]]; information-based services such as [[information]]-generation and information-sharing; and knowledge-based services such as [[Consultant|consultation]], [[education]], [[financial planning]], [[blogging]], and [[designing]].<ref name=twsJun17e>{{cite news\n |author = Peter Busch\n |title= Tacit Knowledge in Organizational Learning\n |publisher= Tacit Knowledge in Organizational Learning\n |quote= see page .. The quaternary sector of industry is the sector of industry that involves the intellectual services. That is research, development, and information.\n |year= 1967\n |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KGd5hL2-rvQC&pg=PT355&lpg=PT355&dq=%22quaternary+sector%22&source=bl&ots=Nj5PiWaZg-&sig=egbw8NcOG00q99uRyMAwX5zTgOY&hl=en&ei=YjUaTI2zK4P7lwew1tDRCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=35&ved=0CMABEOgBMCI#v=onepage&q=%22quaternary%20sector%22&f=false\n |accessdate= 2010-06-17\n}}</ref>\n\nThe quaternary sector is based on pure knowledge and skill of a person. It consists of intellectual industries providing information services, such as [[computing]] and [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] (information and communication technologies), [[consultancy]] (offering advice to [[business]]es) and [[Research and development|R&D]] (research, particularly in scientific fields). According to some definitions, the Quaternary sector includes other ''pure'' services, such as the [[entertainment industry]], and the term has been used{{by whom|date=August 2015}} to describe [[mass media|media]], [[culture]], and [[government]].\n\n[[File:Clark's Sector Model.png|right|thumb|450px|Colin Clark (economist)|[[Colin Clark (economist)|Colin Clark]]'s sector model of an economy undergoing technological change. In later stages, the quaternary sector of the economy grows \u2013 shown in red.]]\n[[File:Criminal Minds scene (Season 6).jpg|thumb|Producing entertainment television]]\n\n\"Quaternary sector\" is a further delineation of the [[three-sector model|three-sector hypothesis]] of [[industry]] in the sense that the ''Quaternary sector'' refers to a part of the third or [[tertiary sector of the economy|tertiary sector]] along with the quinary economic sector. Intellectual services are sometimes regarded as distinct enough to warrant a separate sector and not be considered merely as a part of the tertiary sector.  This sector evolves in well-[[developed country|developed countries]] where the primary and secondary sectors are a minority of the economy, and requires a highly educated workforce.<ref name=twsJun17d>{{cite news|title = ICTs, industry and the new teacher model\n |publisher= Asian Correspondent\n |quote= In Australia, the service sector accounts for 70 per cent of the country's economic activity. Within the service sector, however, more intellectual activities such as government, education, culture and media, can be further defined as the 'quaternary' sector of the economy. These activities are typically not measured in monetary value but they significantly contribute to the economy. \n |date= 2010-06-17\n |url= http://us.asiancorrespondent.com/QUT/icts-industry-and-the-new-teacher-model \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730183257/http://asiancorrespondent.com/30277/icts-industry-and-the-new-teacher-model/|archivedate=July 30, 2012\n |url-status=dead\n |accessdate= 2015-09-09\n}}</ref>\n\nBetween them, the tertiary and quaternary sectors form the largest part of the [[economy of the United Kingdom|UK economy]], employing 76% of the workforce. The number of people who earn their living in these activities is increasing.\nCompanies invest in the Quaternary sector to promote further expansion.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} It is seen{{by whom|date=August 2015}} as a way to generate higher margins or returns on investment.<ref name=twsJun17f>{{cite news\n |author= press release\n |title= TEXT-Fitch: Investment to increase in India's healthcare sector\n |work= Reuters\n |quote = Fitch notes that newly commissioned hospitals and improved occupancy rates at existing ones will drive revenue growth. Better capacity utilisation and increased focus on higher-margin tertiary and quaternary healthcare services are expected to boost profitability, and improve cash flow from operations (CFO).\n |date= February 19, 2010\n |url= http://in.reuters.com/assets/print?aid=INWLB790520100219\n |accessdate= 2015-07-23\n}}\n</ref>\nResearch will be directed{{by whom|date=August 2015}} into cutting costs, tapping into [[market (economics)|markets]], producing innovative ideas, new production methods and methods of [[manufacture]], among others.{{when|date=August 2015}} To many industries, such as the [[pharmaceutical industry]], the sector is the most valuable because it creates future secondary-sector [[brand|branded products]] from which companies may [[profit (accounting)|profit]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Economic sector]]\n* [[Indigo Era]]\n* [[Primary sector of the economy]]\n* [[Secondary sector of the economy]]\n* [[Tertiary sector of the economy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Industries}}\n\n{{industry-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Economic sectors|+4]]\n[[Category:National accounts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Tone|reason=passive voice and bland abstraction, as previously flagged by other editors|date=January 2019}}\n{{Economic sectors}}\n\nThe '''quaternary sector''' is the label used to describe a [[Knowledge economy|knowledge-based]]<ref name=twsJun17c>{{cite news\n |author = Tor Selstad\n |title= The rise of the quaternary sector. The regional dimension of wisdom or knowledge-based services in Norway, 1970\u20131985 - Norsk Geografisk Tidsskrift - Norwegian Journal of Geography - Volume 44, Issue 1\n |publisher= informaworld\n |quote= ... knowledge-based services ...\n |year= 1990\n |url= http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a792213401~tab=citations\n |accessdate= 2010-06-17\n}}</ref> [[economic sector|part]] of the economy, which typically includes knowledge-oriented economic sectors such as [[information technology]], [[mass media|media]], [[research and development]]; information-based services such as [[information]]-generation and information-sharing; and knowledge-based services such as [[Consultant|consultation]], [[education]], [[financial planning]], [[blogging]], and [[designing]].<ref name=twsJun17e>{{cite news\n |author = Peter Busch\n |title= Tacit Knowledge in Organizational Learning\n |publisher= Tacit Knowledge in Organizational Learning\n |quote= see page .. The quaternary sector of industry is the sector of industry that involves the intellectual services. That is research, development, and information.\n |year= 1967\n |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KGd5hL2-rvQC&pg=PT355&lpg=PT355&dq=%22quaternary+sector%22&source=bl&ots=Nj5PiWaZg-&sig=egbw8NcOG00q99uRyMAwX5zTgOY&hl=en&ei=YjUaTI2zK4P7lwew1tDRCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=35&ved=0CMABEOgBMCI#v=onepage&q=%22quaternary%20sector%22&f=false\n |accessdate= 2010-06-17\n}}</ref>\n\nThe quaternary sector is based on pure knowledge and skill of a person. It consists of intellectual industries providing information services, such as [[computing]] and [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] (information and communication technologies), [[consultancy]] (offering advice to [[business]]es) and [[Research and development|R&D]] (research, particularly in scientific fields). According to some definitions, the Quaternary sector includes other ''pure'' services, such as the [[entertainment industry]], and the term has been used{{by whom|date=August 2015}} to describe [[mass media|media]], [[culture]], and [[government]].\n\n[[File:Clark's Sector Model.png|right|thumb|450px|Colin Clark (economist)|[[Colin Clark (economist)|Colin Clark]]'s sector model of an economy undergoing technological change. In later stages, the quaternary sector of the economy grows \u2013 shown in red.]]\n[[File:Criminal Minds scene (Season 6).jpg|thumb|Producing entertainment television]]\n\n\"Quaternary sector\" is a further delineation of the [[three-sector model|three-sector hypothesis]] of [[industry]] in the sense that the ''Quaternary sector'' refers to a part of the third or [[tertiary sector of the economy|tertiary sector]] along with the quinary economic sector. Intellectual services are sometimes regarded as distinct enough to warrant a separate sector and not be considered merely as a part of the tertiary sector.  This sector evolves in well-[[developed country|developed countries]] where the primary and secondary sectors are a minority of the economy, and requires a highly educated workforce.<ref name=twsJun17d>{{cite news|title = ICTs, industry and the new teacher model\n |publisher= Asian Correspondent\n |quote= In Australia, the service sector accounts for 70 per cent of the country's economic activity. Within the service sector, however, more intellectual activities such as government, education, culture and media, can be further defined as the 'quaternary' sector of the economy. These activities are typically not measured in monetary value but they significantly contribute to the economy. \n |date= 2010-06-17\n |url= http://us.asiancorrespondent.com/QUT/icts-industry-and-the-new-teacher-model \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730183257/http://asiancorrespondent.com/30277/icts-industry-and-the-new-teacher-model/|archivedate=July 30, 2012\n |url-status=dead\n |accessdate= 2015-09-09\n}}</ref>\n\nBetween them, the tertiary and quaternary sectors form the largest part of the [[economy of the United Kingdom|UK economy]], employing 76% of the workforce. The number of people who earn their living in these activities is increasing.\nCompanies invest in the Quaternary sector to promote further expansion.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} It is seen{{by whom|date=August 2015}} as a way to generate higher margins or returns on investment.<ref name=twsJun17f>{{cite news\n |author= press release\n |title= TEXT-Fitch: Investment to increase in India's healthcare sector\n |work= Reuters\n |quote = Fitch notes that newly commissioned hospitals and improved occupancy rates at existing ones will drive revenue growth. Better capacity utilisation and increased focus on higher-margin tertiary and quaternary healthcare services are expected to boost profitability, and improve cash flow from operations (CFO).\n |date= February 19, 2010\n |url= http://in.reuters.com/assets/print?aid=INWLB790520100219\n |accessdate= 2015-07-23\n}}\n</ref>\nResearch will be directed{{by whom|date=August 2015}} into cutting costs, tapping into [[market (economics)|markets]], producing innovative ideas, new production methods and methods of [[manufacture]], among others.{{when|date=August 2015}} To many industries, such as the [[pharmaceutical industry]], the sector is the most valuable because it creates future secondary-sector [[brand|branded products]] from which companies may [[profit (accounting)|profit]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Indigo Era]]\n* [[Economic sector]]\n* [[Primary sector]]\n* [[Secondary sector]]\n* [[Tertiary sector]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Industries}}\n\n{{industry-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Economic sectors|+4]]\n[[Category:National accounts]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternary_sector_of_the_economy"}
{"title_page": "Shark attack prevention", "text_new": "There are a range of '''shark attack prevention''' techniques employed to reduce the risk of [[shark attack]] and keep people safe. They include removing sharks by various fishing methods, separating people and sharks, as well as observation, education and various technology-based solutions.\n\nTechniques that involve [[shark culling|culling sharks]] are contentious.  Environmental groups have voiced concern over the impact of reduced shark numbers on ocean ecosystems and the problem of by-catch of other marine life, particularly endangered species.<ref name=\"ausmarine\"/><ref name=\"SSQld\"/><ref name=\"Theguardian1\"/><ref name=\"Meyer\"/><ref name=\"Schetzer\"/> Because sharks are important to the ecosystem, killing them harms the ecosystem.<ref name=\"cullconserve\"/><ref>https://eu.oceana.org/en/importance-sharks Eu.oceana.org. ''The Importance of Sharks in the Ecosystem.'' Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Schetzer\"/>\n\n==Nets==\n\n===Shark net===\n\n{{Main|Shark net}}\n\nThe majority of [[shark net]]s used are [[Gillnetting|gillnets]], which is a wall of netting that hangs in the water and captures the targeted sharks by entanglement.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/interactions/gear/gillnet.htm|title=Gillnets: Fishing Gear and Risks to Protected Species|accessdate=6 January 2017|archivedate=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101002810/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/interactions/gear/gillnet.htm|publisher=United States Government|author=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|url-status=live|date=18 February 2014}}</ref> The nets may be as much as {{convert|186|m|ft}} long, set at a depth of {{convert|6|m|ft}}, have a mesh size of {{convert|500|mm|in}} and are designed to catch sharks longer than {{convert|2|m|ft}} in length.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/fisheries/services/shark-control-program/shark-control-equipment-and-locations|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|title=Shark control equipment and locations|archivedate=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101091020/https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/fisheries/services/shark-control-program/shark-control-equipment-and-locations|publisher=Queensland Government|author=Department of Agriculture and Fisheries|date=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShark nets do not offer complete protection but work on the principle of \"fewer sharks, fewer attacks\". They reduce occurrence via shark mortality. Shark nets such as those in [[New South Wales]] are designed to entangle and kill sharks and other animals that pass near them.<ref name=\"sealife\"/> Historical shark attack figures suggest that the use of shark nets does markedly reduce the incidence of shark attack when implemented on a regular and consistent basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880|title=Can governments protect people from killer sharks?|website=ABC News|date=22 December 2013|url-status=live|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=5 January 2017|archivedate=31 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031175236/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880}}</ref><ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref name =\"Dudley\"/><ref name=\"SAJS\" />\n\nA downside with shark nets is that they do result in [[bycatch]], including threatened and endangered species.<ref name=\"cullconserve\">{{citation|url=https://briantissot.com/2015/08/20/shark-attacks-and-the-surfers-dilemma-cull-or-conserve/|date=20 August 2015|title=Shark Attacks and the Surfer's Dilemma: Cull or Conserve|last=Tissot|first=Brian|url-status=live|accessdate=5 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122154405/https://briantissot.com/2015/08/20/shark-attacks-and-the-surfers-dilemma-cull-or-conserve/|archivedate=22 November 2016|website=Dr Abalone}}</ref> Between September 2017 and April 2018, 403 animals were killed in the nets in [[New South Wales]], including 10 critically endangered [[grey nurse shark]]s, 7 [[dolphin]]s, 7 [[green turtle]]s and 14 [[great white shark]]s.<ref name=\"swellnet\">http://www.swellnet.com/news/swellnet-dispatch/2018/08/04/sydney-shark-nets-set-stay-despite-drumline-success Swellnet.com. ''Sydney shark nets set to stay despite drumline success.'' Bruce Mackenzie. August 4, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> However note that [[bycatch]] from shark nets is minor compared to bycatch from commercial fishing<ref name=\"theherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|title=Beyond the panic: the facts about shark nets|first=Australian Community Media - Fairfax|last=Media|date=8 November 2016|publisher=|accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Bett\">{{cite journal |last1=Stephanie M. Bettis |title=Shark Bycatch in Commercial Fisheries: A Global Perspective |journal=Nova Southeastern University |date=July 2017 |url=https://nsuworks.nova.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com.au/&httpsredir=1&article=1331&context=cnso_stucap |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref> with estimates of 50 million sharks caught unintentionally each year.<ref name=\"Sharksav\">{{cite web |title=Shark fin trade myths and truths |url=http://www.sharksavers.org/files/8613/3185/9956/Shark_Bycatch_FACT_SHEET_Shark_Savers.pdf |website=Sharksavers |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nTotal cost for the shark netting program in [[New South Wales]] for the 2009/10 year was approximately {{AUD|1 million}}, which included the cost of the nets, contractors, observers and shark technicians, shark meshing equipment (dolphin pingers and whale alarms etc.), and compliance audit activities.<ref name=\"NSWGOV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/623400/Report-into-the-NSW-Shark-Meshing-Program.pdf |title=Report into the NSW Shark Meshing (Bather Protection) Program |author=Green, M., Ganassin, C. and Reid, D. D. |publisher=State of New South Wales through NSW Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> For the 51 beaches protected,<ref name=\"NSWGOV\"/> this represents a financial cost of approximately {{AUD|20,000}} per beach per year.\n\nShark nets have been criticized by environmentalists and conservationists; they say shark nets damage the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"sealife\">http://www.sealifetrust.org.au/news/latest/shark-nets-australia-work ''Shark nets in Australia \u2013 what are they and how do they work?'' Sealifetrust.org.au. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"sharkangels\">http://www.sharkangels.org/index.php/media/news/157-shark-nets ''Shark Nets.'' Sharkangels.org. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"cullconserve\"/> The current net program in New South Wales has been described as being \"extremely destructive\" to marine life;<ref>https://www.buzzfeed.com/elfyscott/heres-what-you-need-to-know-about-australias-smart-drum ''Here's What You Need To Know About Australia's SMART Drum Lines Being Used To Prevent Shark Attacks.'' Elfy Scott. July 5, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> it has also been called \"outdated and ineffective\".<ref name=\"swellnet\"/>  The New South Wales government prohibits people from rescuing entangled animals \u2014 this prohibition has been called \"heartless and cruel\".<ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/nsw/2018/01/09/greens-shark-nets-rays/ ''Threat to cut shark nets if government fails to act.'' Rachel Eddie. January 9, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Shark barrier===\n[[File:Coogee Beach gnangarra-215.jpg|thumb|[[Coogee, Western Australia|Coogee Beach]] shark barrier floats and jetty]]\n\n{{Main|Shark barrier}}\n\nA [[shark barrier]] (otherwise known as a \"shark-proof enclosure\" or \"beach enclosure\") is seabed-to-surface protective barrier that is placed around a beach to separate people from sharks. Shark barriers form a fully enclosed swimming area that prevents sharks from entering.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news|last=Meerman|first=Ruben|title=Shark nets |website=ABC Science|date=16 January 2009|url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2002/03/07/2116717.htm|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129034201/http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2002/03/07/2116717.htm|archivedate=29 November 2016}}</ref> Shark barrier design has evolved from rudimentary fencing materials to netted structures held in place with buoys and anchors. Recent designs have used plastics to increase strength and versatility.\n\nWhen deployed in sheltered areas shark barriers offer complete protection and are seen as a more environmentally friendly option as they largely avoid bycatch. However barriers are not effective on surf beaches because they usually disintegrate in the swell and so are normally constructed only around sheltered areas such as harbour beaches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/fact-file-protecting-people-from-shark-attacks/5164882|date=5 January 2015|title=Fact File: Protecting people from shark attacks|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nA [[Middleton Beach shark barrier|shark barrier installed at Middleton beach]] in [[Albany, Western Australia]] cost {{AUD|340,000}} to install, with annual maintenance budgeted at {{AUD|30,000}} per annum.<ref name=ABC1>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-16/albany-council-awards-shark-barrier-contract/7033664|title=Albany shark barrier contract goes to Australian firm|date=16 December 2015|accessdate=28 December 2016|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> On [[R\u00e9union]] Island in 2015 two shark proof enclosures cost \u20ac2&nbsp;million to install and \u20ac1&nbsp;million a year to maintain.<ref name=Schuetze/>\n\n==Drum lines==\n{{Main|Drum line (shark control)}}\nA [[Drum line (shark control)|drum line]] is an unmanned aquatic trap used to lure and capture large sharks using baited hooks. They are typically deployed near popular swimming beaches with the intention of reducing the number of sharks in the vicinity and therefore the probability of shark attack. Drum lines were first deployed to protect users of the marine environment from sharks in [[Queensland]], Australia in 1962. During this time, they were just as successful in reducing the frequency of shark attacks as the shark nets.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www2.dpi.qld.gov.au/extra/pdf/fishweb/sharksafetyreport.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123173415/http://www2.dpi.qld.gov.au/extra/pdf/fishweb/sharksafetyreport.pdf|archivedate=23 January 2014|accessdate=6 January 2017|title=A Report on the Queensland Shark Safety Program|date=March 2006|publisher=Queensland Government|author=Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref name =\"Dudley\">{{cite journal|last1=Dudley, S.F.J.|title=A comparison of the shark control programs of New South Wales and Queensland (Australia) and KwaZulu-Natal (South Africa)|journal=Ocean Coast Manag|volume=34|date=1997|issue=1|pages=1\u201327|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223563025|doi=10.1016/S0964-5691(96)00061-0}}</ref> More recently, drumlines have also been used with great success in [[Recife]], Brazil where the number of attacks has been shown to have reduced by 97% when the drumlines are deployed.<ref name=HazinAfonso/> While shark nets and drum lines share the same purpose, drum lines are more effective at targeting the three sharks that are considered most dangerous to swimmers: the [[bull shark]], [[tiger shark]] and [[great white shark]].<ref name=Dudleyetal>{{cite journal |first1=Sheldon F.J.|last1=Dudley|first2=R.C.|last2=Haestier |last3=Cox|first3=K.R.|first4=M.|last4= Murray |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MF98026.pdf |title=Shark control: Experimental fishing with baited drumlines |accessdate=22 January 2010|journal=Marine and Freshwater Research|volume=49|issue=7|date=January 1998}}</ref> [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]]s can also be utilised to move sharks, which greatly reduces mortality of sharks and [[bycatch]] to less than 2%.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\" />\n\nIn 2014 a three-month trial utilising up to 60 drum lines in [[Western Australia]] cost {{AUD|1.28 million}}.<ref name=\"WA-cost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dpc.wa.gov.au/Publications/Documents/Review%20-%20Western%20Australia%20Shark%20Hazard%20Mitigation%20Drum%20Line%20Program%202013-14.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102171105/https://www.dpc.wa.gov.au/Publications/Documents/Review%20-%20Western%20Australia%20Shark%20Hazard%20Mitigation%20Drum%20Line%20Program%202013-14.pdf|archivedate=2 January 2017|title=Review: Western Australia Shark Hazard Mitigation Drum Line Program 2013/14|publisher=Government of Western Australia|author=Department of the Premier and Cabinet |accessdate=3 January 2017|date=June 2014}}</ref>\n\nDrum line programmes that involve [[culling]] have been criticized for being environmentally destructive and [[speciesism|speciesist]], and have sparked public demonstrations and vocal opposition, particularly from environmentalists, animal welfare advocates and ocean activists.<ref name=\"ausmarine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausmarinescience.com/marine-science-basics/marine-biology/sharks/|title=Sharks|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SSQld\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seashepherd.org.au/apex-harmony/overview/queensland.html|title=Queensland - Overview|website=www.seashepherd.org.au|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Theguardian1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/feb/12/was-serious-threat-shark-policy-condemned-by-senate|title=Western Australia's 'serious threat' shark policy condemned by Senate|first=Calla|last=Wahlquist|date=12 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"Meyer\">{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/western-australias-shark-culls-lack-bite-and-science-21371|title=Western Australia's shark culls lack bite (and science)|first=Carl|last=Meyer|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> Conservationists say killing sharks on drum lines harms the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"Schetzer\">Alana Schetzer (8 May 2017). http://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/sharks-how-a-cull-could-ruin-an-ecosystem ''\"Sharks: How a cull could ruin an ecosystem\".'' Science Matters. University of Melbourne \u2013 via Pursuit. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> In 2018, endangered [[hammerhead shark]]s were found dead on Queensland's drum lines.<ref name=\"ntd\"/> The current drum line program in [[Queensland]] has been called \"outdated, cruel and ineffective\".<ref name=\"ntd\">https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ ''Endangered Hammerhead Sharks Dead on Drum Line in Great Barrier Reef.'' Jack Phillips. Ntd.tv. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> However environmental damage from drumlines is minor compared to commercial fishing<ref name=\"theherald\" /><ref name=\"Bett\" /> with estimates of 50 million sharks caught unintentionally each year.<ref name=\"Sharksav\" />\n\n==Other protection methods==\n[[File:Living in a shark-eat-shark world 150617-M-RT812-001.jpg|thumb|A sign at Pyramid Rock Beach in [[Hawaii]] warning about a shark sighting, 2015]]\n\n===Moving sharks===\nMoving sharks is a way of reducing shark attacks and reducing shark mortality, by capturing,  transporting and releasing the sharks further shore. In Recife, Brazil, sharks that were near shore were captured and physically moved offshore with 70% of potentially aggressive sharks and 78% of other animals caught released alive.<ref name=\"HazinAfonso\" /> Sharks that were moved did not return to the same location.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/shark-week-science-empathy-meet-shark-storm-shark-exile-172736463.html | title=Shark Week: Science and Empathy Meet in 'Shark Storm' and 'Shark Exile'}}</ref> This technique has also been successfully demonstrated in the NSW North Coast [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]] trial (Australia) where 99% of targeted sharks and 98% of other animals caught were released alive.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\">{{cite web |title=NSW North Coast SMART drumline data |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/fishing/sharks/management/smart-drumlines |website=NSW Government: Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe West Australian Government are now trialling the same technique along [[Western Australia]]'s South West coast, near [[Gracetown]].<ref name=\"WA_Smart_trial\">{{cite web |title=SCIENTIFIC NON-LETHAL SMART DRUMLINE TRIAL |url=https://www.sharksmart.com.au/research/smart-drumline-trial/ |website=Sharksmart |publisher=Government of West Australia |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sharks to be caught on SMART drum lines off WA's South West after Labor U-turn |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-14/shark-attacks-prompt-wa-to-conduct-smart-drum-line-trial/10117230 |accessdate=14 August 2018 |agency=ABC News |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Shark tagging and tracking===\nAcross the world a sample of sharks have been tagged with electronic devices that transmit their location.<ref name=\"Tracking\">{{cite web|title=Tracking sharks|url=http://www.trackingsharks.com/track-sharks/|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>  Acoustic tags transmit pulses which are detected by underwater listening stations when the sharks swim close by, typically within 500 metres.<ref name=\"WA_monitor\"/><ref name=\"Options\"/> Fin-mounted satellite tags are also commonly used.<ref name=\"Options\"/> These tags allow shark movements and behaviour to be monitored and studied and swimmers and surfers can be warned if a shark is detected close to shore.<ref name=\"WA_monitor\">{{cite web|title=Shark monitoring network|url=http://sharksmart.com.au/research/shark-monitoring-network/|website=Sharksmart|publisher=West Australian Government|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHowever a limitation with the system is the tagging will only highlight a very small portion of the dangerous sharks present.<ref name=\"Options\"/> It also may lead people into a false sense of security.<ref name=\"Options\"/>\n\n===Shark spotting===\nShark-spotting programs using drones, fixed wing aircraft, helicopters, [[beach patrol]]s, observation towers and even blimps, are being used and trialled in various locations across the globe.<ref name=\"Options\">{{cite news|last1=Turnbull|first1=Samantha|title=Protecting humans from sharks: What are the options?|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-01/protecting-humans-from-sharks-what-are-the-options/7979206|accessdate=28 May 2017|publisher=ABC News|date=3 November 2016}}</ref> However visibility issues with water clarity can be a problem particularly with aerial patrols, which have been found to identify less than 20% of sharks present.<ref name=\"NSWGOV\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Robbins, William D. |display-authors=etal |title=Experimental evaluation of shark detection rates by aerial observers|journal=PLoS ONE |volume=9 |issue=2|date=2014|page=e83456|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0083456|pmid=24498258|pmc=3911894}}</ref>  There is also the financial cost of hiring aircraft and/or personnel to conduct the surveillance.<ref name=\"Options\"/>\n\n=== Shark sonar ===\nIn September 2015, a shark sonar created by [[Ric Richardson]] was tested in [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay]], Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian first: sonar shark detection trial in Byron Bay|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/shark-sonar-trial-may-help-with-early-warning-for-/2779966/|website=Northern Star}}</ref> It is a passive sonar device that does not interfere with animals like dolphins. The final device will sit on the ocean floor and can detect sharks over 2,5 meters long when they are 100 meters away. An alarm will notify people that they have to go out of the water. Other shark sonar systems are also been tested and showing promising results.<ref>{{cite web |title=Evaluation of Clever Buoy Shark Detection System |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/815866/evaluation-of-clever-buoy-shark-detection-system-summary.pdf |website=New South Wales Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Personal shark repellents ===\n\n{{Main|Shark repellant}}\n\nA shark repellent is any method of driving [[shark]]s away from an area and includes [[magnetic shark repellent]], [[electropositive shark repellent]]s, electrical repellents (including [[Shark Shield]]) and [[semiochemical]]s. One example is a product called Anti-Shark 100<ref name=\"Shark_tec\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Shark 100 Product Overview|url=https://www.sharktecdefense.com|website=SharkTec|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> which is an aerosol can that contains an extract of dead shark tissue. There is a range of evidence that supports the effectiveness of this product.<ref name=\"Life_hacker\">{{cite web|last1=Francis|first1=Hannah|title=Do Shark Repellents Actually Work?|url=https://www.lifehacker.com.au/2016/01/do-shark-repellents-actually-work/|website=Lifehacker|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=2016-01-04}}</ref> Chemical repellents have been researched since before the 1940s, some of which have raised concerns as to their effectiveness. The semiochemical used in the Anti-shark 100 product have been independently tested & verified on Caribbean reef sharks, however there are concerns it may attract Tiger and White sharks.<ref name =\"NSW\">{{cite journal|last1=Cardno|title=Shark Deterrents and Detectors: Review of Bather Protection Technologies|journal=Prepared for NSW Department of Primary Industries|date=October 2015|pages=12|url=http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/578999/cardno-review-of-bather-protection-technologies.pdf|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOther examples of personal shark protection technologies include wearing interruption patterned or camouflage wetsuits,<ref>{{cite news|last=Starr|first=Michelle |url=http://www.cnet.com.au/aussies-design-shark-proof-wetsuits-339344936.htm |title=Aussies design shark-proof wetsuits|website=C-Net|location=Australia |date=22 July 2013|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> magnetic repellents incorporating a small magnet in a band worn on the wrist or ankle,<ref name=\"Life_hacker\"/> acoustic repellents that mimic the sound of [[orcas]]<ref name=\"Choice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.choice.com.au/health-and-body/diet-and-fitness/surfing-and-snowboarding/articles/shark-repellents-review|title=Under attack: Do shark repellents work?|last1=Doyle|first1=Chris|date=2016-10-03|website=Choice|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> and changing surf board colours.<ref name=\"Options\"/> However none of the products associated with these technologies have been independently tested.<ref name=\"Choice\"/><ref name=\"Options\"/><ref name=\"Life_hacker\"/>\n\n====Shark shield====\n\n{{Main|Shark Shield}}\n\nShark Shield is a personal electronic device that creates an [[Electro magnetic field|electromagnetic field]] to deter [[shark attack]]s and is used by [[Surfing|surfers]], [[scuba diver]]s, [[spearfishing]], and ocean [[kayak fishing]]. It has been considered one of the few electrical devices on the market that has performed independent trials to determine the effectiveness <ref name=\"Kempster\">{{cite journal|display-authors=etal|vauthors=Kempster RM, Egeberg CA, Hart NS, Ryan L, Chapuis L, Kerr CC|date=1 June 2016|title=How Close is too Close? The Effect of a Non-Lethal Electric Shark Deterrent on White Shark Behaviour|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=11|issue=7|page=e0157717|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0157717|pmc=4930202|pmid=27368059}}</ref><ref name=\"Huveneers\">{{citation|last=Huveneers|first=C.|title=Effects of the Shark Shield electric deterrent on the behaviour of white sharks Carcharodon carcharias|date=June 2012|url=http://www.sardi.sa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/173876/Risk_Assessment_of_the_Shark_Shield_Report_-_FINAL_19_06_2012.pdf|location=Australia|publisher=SARDI|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> at deterring shark attacks.<ref name=\"Choice\" />  However note that the Shark Shield does not work in all situations<ref name=\"Kempster\" /><ref name=\"ABC_sa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2012/06/20/3529306.htm|title=SA researchers trial effectiveness of electronic shark deterrent devices on Great Whites|last1=Williamson|first1=Brett|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Huveneers\" /> and divers have been attacked whilst wearing Shark Shield.<ref name=\"Choice\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portlincolntimes.com.au/story/1608925/clarkson-was-wearing-shark-shield/|title=Clarkson was wearing shark shield|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=2 June 2017|publisher=Port Lincoln Times}}</ref>\n\nThe West Australian government has also announced that they are supporting the Shark Shield FREEDOM 7 and the Ocean Guardian FREEDOM+ Surf via a $200 subsidiary.<ref name=\"Sharksmart_faq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sharksmart.com.au/staying-safe/rebate-faqs/|title=SHARK DETERRENT REBATE - FAQ|website=Sharksmart|publisher=West Australian Government|accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Protection by dolphins ===\nThere are documented instances of [[bottlenose dolphin]]s protecting humans from shark attacks, one off the coast of [[New Zealand]] in 2004<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4034383.stm | work=BBC News | title=Dolphins prevent NZ shark attack | date=23 November 2004 | accessdate=6 April 2010 | first=Phil | last=Mercer}}</ref> and one attack on a surfer in northern [[California]] in August 2007.<ref name=\"msnbc1\">{{cite web|last=Celizic |first=Mike |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21689083/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109080539/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21689083/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 November 2007 |title=Dolphins rescue surfer from shark - TODAY People - People: Tales of survival - TODAYshow.com |publisher=MSNBC |date=8 November 2007 |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> There is no accepted explanation for this behavior; as mentioned in the ''Journal of Zoology'', \"The importance of interactions between sharks and cetaceans has been a subject of much conjecture, but few studies have addressed these interactions\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Predator\u2013prey and competitive interactions between sharks (order Selachii) and dolphins (suborder Odontoceti): a review |doi=10.1017/S0952836901000061 |volume=253 |journal=Journal of Zoology |pages=53\u201368|year = 2001|last1 = Heithaus|first1 = Michael R.|citeseerx=10.1.1.404.130 }}</ref> In some cases, sharks have been seen attacking, or trying to attack dolphins.<ref>http://www.abcactionnews.com/news/local/story/Rehabilitated-dolphin-dies-after-shark-attack/Os5uEUUiFU2NukbdnqiZXQ.cspx</ref>  The presence of porpoises does not indicate the absence of sharks as both eat the same food<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncseagrant.org/home/coastwatch/coastwatch-articles?task=showArticle&id=570 |title=North Carolina Sea Grant \u2013 Coastwatch Articles |publisher=Ncseagrant.org |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> and surfers have been attacked by sharks whilst in the presence of dolphins.<ref>{{cite news|last1=PerthNow|title=Bunbury man tells of close encounter with shark|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/western-australia/bunbury-man-tells-of-close-encounter-with-shark/news-story/7e58f37ba2c46f969a6af4357b0fd8b9|accessdate=20 June 2017|newspaper=Sunday Times|date=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== By country ==\n=== Australia ===\n==== Queensland and New South Wales ====\n[[File:Graph of sharks caught in Queensland's Shark Control Program (by type) July 1997- June 2014.PNG|thumb|Graph of sharks caught in Queensland's shark control program (by type) July 1997- June 2014]]\n\nIn Queensland and NSW systematic long term shark control programs using shark nets and drumlines are utilised to reduce the risk of shark attack. Since 1936 sharks nets have been utilised off Sydney beaches.<ref name=\"Coastwatch-article\">{{cite web |url=http://52.64.240.87/environment/20632/nick-carroll-on-beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets |title=Nick Carroll On-Beyond the Panic, The Facts about Shark Nets |last=Carroll|first= Nick |publisher=Coastal Watch |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> Nowadays they are employed on both NSW and Queensland beaches; 83 beaches are meshed in Queensland compared with NSW's current 51.<ref name=\"Coastwatch-article\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|date=8 November 2016|newspaper=Newcastle Herald|title=Nick Carroll: the facts about shark nets|accessdate=5 January 2017|publisher=Fairfax Media|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112082645/http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|archivedate=12 November 2016|url-status=live|first=Nick|last=Carroll}}</ref>\n\nThe technique of setting drum lines is also used in Queensland and New South Wales, where they have been used in association with shark nets. Before 1962, there were 82 recorded attacks. Since the policy was implemented there has only been one recorded death, at [[Amity Point, Queensland|Amity Point]] in January 2006. 21-year-old Sarah Kate Whiley was attacked by as many as three sharks in Rainbow Channel. The attack occurred in an unpatrolled area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-01-09/lifesavers-warn-swimmers-off-amity-point/775902 |title=Lifesavers warn swimmers off Amity Point|website=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 January 2006|archivedate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028145649/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-01-09/lifesavers-warn-swimmers-off-amity-point/775902|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Queensland Fisheries Minister [[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]] has described the longevity of the netting and drum line program as being \"a good indicator that it had the support of most Queenslanders\".<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|last=King|first=Rihanna|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/21017928// |title=Drum lines 'keep State safe'|newspaper=The West Australian|date=25 January 2014|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe baited drum lines attract sharks from within a 3&ndash;5&nbsp;km radius, preventing sharks from reaching swimming areas. They also capture less bycatch than shark nets.<ref name=Dudleyetal/>\n\nThere were a total of 97 fatalities attributed to shark attacks in Queensland between 1858 and 2014. In New South Wales there were a total of 96 fatalities attributed to shark attack between 1771 and 2014.\n\nThe current shark-killing programs in Queensland and New South Wales have been called [[shark culling|culls]], and have been criticized by environmentalists, who say killing sharks harms the marine ecosystem.<ref name=\"marineconservation\"/><ref name=\"ntd\"/> Between 1950 and 2008, 577 great white sharks and 352 tiger sharks were killed in the nets in New South Wales \u2014 also during this period, 15,135 marine animals were caught and killed in the nets, including whales, turtles, rays, dolphins, and dugongs.<ref name=\"marineconservation\">https://web.archive.org/web/20181002102324/https://www.marineconservation.org.au/pages/shark-culling.html Marineconservation.org.au. Shark culling (archived). Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref> In Queensland, from 2001 to 2018, a total of 10,480 sharks were killed on lethal drum lines.<ref>https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/queensland-government-kills-sharks-faces-court-challenge Queensland Government Kills Sharks, Faces Court Challenge. maritime-executive.com. September 4, 2018. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180904151759/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/queensland-government-kills-sharks-faces-court-challenge archived] from the original on 2018-09-04. Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref>\n\n===== NSW North Coast shark net and smart drumline trial =====\n\nFollowing 11 shark attacks along the NSW north coast between 2014 and 2016, including two fatalities,<ref>{{cite news|title=Episode 1: The Anger|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/ballina-lennox-byron-shark-crisis/news-story/70abd956652869c53a7d1d464ce971c6|accessdate=23 March 2018|newspaper=The Australian|date=5 December 2016}}</ref> [[Shark nets]] and [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumlines]] were deployed in December 2016 to cover five additional beaches along the NSW North Coast in a two-year trial. Five nets were deployed off Seven Mile Beach off Lennox Head; Sharpes, Shelly and Lighthouse beaches off Ballina; and Main Beach at Evans Head.<ref name=\"NCSN_Trial\">{{cite web|title=North Coast Shark Net Trial: Summary|url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/fishing/sharks/management/shark-net-trial|website=NSW Department of Primary Industry|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> Twenty five drumlines were also deployed among nets at Ballina and Evans Head beaches (15 off Ballina; 10 off Evans Head).<ref name=\"NCSN_Trial\" /> The trial was successful with no shark attacks occurring at the protected beaches.<ref name=\"FAQ\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Shark nets will return to NSW's north coast beaches|url=https://www.tweeddailynews.com.au/news/shark-nets-will-return-nsws-north-coast-beaches/3218840/|accessdate=23 March 2018|publisher=Tweed Daily News|date=1 September 2017}}</ref> The [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]] caught 230 targeted sharks with 99% of targeted sharks and 98% of other animals caught were released alive.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\"/> The SMART drumlines are now being expanded to other NSW regions.<ref name=\"FAQ\">{{cite web |title=SMART Drumlines: Frequently asked Questions |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/732624/SMART-drumlines-faqs.pdf |website=NSW Department of Primary Industries |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> The shark net trial caught 11 targeted sharks and had a 54% survival rate for all animals caught and will not be continued.<ref name=\"NSW_Trial_Final\">{{cite journal |last1=NSW Department of Primary Industries |title=Second NSW north coast shark-meshing trial Final Report |date=August 2018 |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/829458/second-north-coast-shark-meshing-final-report.pdf |accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Western Australia ====\n[[File:Albany Shark barrier.JPG|thumb|[[Middleton Beach shark barrier]], [[Albany, Western Australia]]]]\n{{Main|Western Australian shark cull}}\nIn August 2018 following continual shark attacks and public pressure the West Australian state government announced a 12-month trial of [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|\"smart\" drumlines]] along [[Western Australia]]'s South West coast, near [[Gracetown]].<ref name=\"WA_trial\" >{{cite news |title=Sharks to be caught on SMART drum lines off WA's South West after Labor U-turn |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-14/shark-attacks-prompt-wa-to-conduct-smart-drum-line-trial/10117230 |accessdate=14 August 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nWestern Australia also deploys shark enclosures in a range of locations<ref>{{citation|title=Shark attacks in Australia: a timeline|publisher=Australian Geographic|date=2014|url= http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/scienceenvironment/2014/01/shark-attacks-in-australia-a-timeline/|accessdate= 7 January 2015}}</ref> as well as aerial shark spotters, beach patrols, shark tagging efforts and associated tracking and notification systems.\n\nThere were a total of 114 unprovoked shark attacks in West Australia between 1870 and 2016,<ref>[http://www.sharkattackfile.net/incidentlog.htm Global shark attack file > Incident Log] ''SharkAttackFile.net'' Accessed 2018-08-14</ref> including 16 fatalities since 2000.<ref name=Aust>{{cite news |last1=Carmody |first1=James |title=Fatal shark attack near Esperance off WA's south-east coast claims diver's life |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-05/shark-attack-reported-near-esperance-off-wa-south-east-coast/11842420 |accessdate=5 January 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== South Australia ====\nIn [[South Australia]], spotter planes and a small number of patrolled swimming beaches are the only methods used to mitigate the risk of shark attack. On 6 February 2014, Port Lincoln tuna \"[[Business magnate|baron]]\" [[Hagen Stehr]] expressed his support for the [[Western Australian shark cull]]. He also stated that his business' spotter planes had observed increases in great white shark numbers off the west coast of [[Eyre Peninsula]]. He acknowledged that his tuna farming operations attract some sharks. He told ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' that he believed \"selected culling of sharks is a must. It is crazy stuff to put them under protection so it becomes a major offence to kill them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Austin|first=Nigel |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/port-lincoln-tuna-baron-hagen-stehr-says-shark-culling-is-a-must/story-fni6uo1m-1226820051425|title=Port Lincoln tuna baron Hagen Stehr says shark culling is a must|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|location= South Australia |date=7 February 2014|accessdate=9 February 2014}}</ref> Critics of Stehr's stance note that a cull of sharks in SA would be beneficial to his business, as tuna is a major source of food for sharks. Shark attack survivor turned conservationist [[Rodney Fox]] has spoken out against the cull, saying \"When a shark attacks someone, we go 'the shark needs to be punished'. They don't live under our laws. It's a different world down there and it should be treated differently.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dempster|first=Alice |url=http://www.victorharbortimes.com.au/story/2099778/rodney-fox-visits-victor-harbor/ |title=Rodney Fox visits Victor Harbor|newspaper=The Times|location=Victor Harbor, South Australia |date=19 February 2014|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt September 2014, there had been a total of 82 [[shark attacks in South Australia]] since 1836, including 20 fatalities.<ref>[http://www.sharkattackfile.net/incidentlog.htm Global shark attack file > Incident Log] ''SharkAttackFile.net'' Accessed 2014-02-09.</ref>\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[File:Shark spotting information sign, Noordhoek Beach, ZA.jpg|thumb|upright|Shark spotting information sign at ''Noordhoek'' Beach in [[South Africa]] (2015)]]\nIn [[KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa a long term shark control program utilising a combination of shark nets and drum lines are used to mitigate the risk of shark attack. The region's shark attack statistics primarily reflect the effectiveness of netting, as drum lines were only introduced recently, following their successful use for over 40 years in Queensland, Australia. The [[KwaZulu-Natal Sharks Board]] (KZNSB) says \"Both types of equipment function by reducing shark numbers in the vicinity of protected beaches, thereby lowering the probability of encounters between sharks and people at those beaches.\" The KZNSB says, \"At [[Durban]], from 1943 until the installation of shark nets in 1952, there were seven fatal attacks. Since the installation of nets there have been no fatalities at Durban and no incidents resulting in serious injury.\" The KZNSB also says, \"At KwaZulu-Natal's other [netted] beaches, from 1940 until most of those beaches were first netted in the 1960s, there were 16 fatal attacks and 11 resulting in serious injury. In the three decades since nets were installed, there have been no fatal attacks at those beaches and only four resulting in serious injury.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shark.co.za/SharkNetsMore|title=Shark Nets, Drum Lines & Safe Swimming|author=KwaZulu-Natal Shark Board|location=South Africa|accessdate=3 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128015833/http://www.shark.co.za/SharkNetsMore|archivedate=28 January 2014}}</ref> The presence of nets has greatly reduced the number of shark attacks along Natal beaches.<ref name=\"SAJS\">{{cite journal |title=Shark attacks on the South African coast between 1960 and 1990 |journal=South African Journal of Science |date=October 1991 |volume=87 |issue=10 |pages=513\u2013518 |url=https://journals.co.za/content/sajsci/87/10/AJA00382353_7199 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> It is unclear whether more sharks caught on drum lines survive when compared to shark net captures in KwaZulu-Natal, but the lines have shown reduced non-target species bycatch. Drum lines set in the region are baited with 500 grams of meat per hook and are believed to only attract sharks from several hundred metres away.<ref>{{citation|last=Kearney|first=Alison|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~spea/pubs/undergrad-honors/volume-5/kearney_allison.pdf|title=Environmental Impacts of Shark Nets on the KwaZulu-Natal Coast|publisher=Indiana University|location=USA|date=2011}}</ref>\n\nSeasonal and temporary bathing bans and \"discretionary bathing\" are additional strategies employed in the region. Bans often follow net displacement or damage due to storms or swell, or net removal due to whale stranding. Nets are also removed during the annual [[sardine run]] to limit the degree of bycatch during the event. Pressure from the tourism industry to reinstate nets during the sardine run has previously proven \"disastrous\", resulting in large numbers of shark and dolphin mortalities.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe \"shark control\" program in KwaZulu-Natal has been called \"archaic\" and \"disastrous to the ecosystem\" (by environmentalists).<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> In a 30-year period, more than 33,000 sharks have been killed in KwaZulu-Natal's shark-killing program \u2014 also during this period, 2,211 turtles, 8,448 rays, and 2,310 dolphins were killed.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> Environmental groups say KwaZulu-Natal's \"shark control\" program is unethical and harms the marine ecosystem.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> Activists in Durban say that Durban's shark nets serve no purpose.<ref>Cole, Barbara (August 3, 2018). https://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/durban-activists-claim-shark-nets-serve-no-purpose-16389703 \"Durban activists claim 'shark nets serve no purpose\". iol.co.za.  Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== USA ===\nIn [[Hawaii]], seven short term shark culls utilising [[Long line fishing|long-lines]] took place between 1959 and 1976. <ref name =\"Curtis-2012\">{{cite web |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260382789_Responding_to_the_risk_of_white_shark_attack_Updated_statistics_prevention_control_methods_and_recommendations |title=Responding to the risk of white shark attack: updated statistics, prevention, control, methods and recommendation.  Chapter 29 In: M. L. Domeier (ed). Global Perspectives on the Biology and Life History of the White Shark |author=Curtis |display-authors=etal |date=2012|publisher=CRC Press. Boca Raton, FL. |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> During this time, 4,668 sharks were caught, at a cost of US$300,000. Although the Hawaiian resident and tourist human population increased dramatically, the number of shark attacks remained constant (in contrast to [[Florida]], where the number of shark attacks has increased in line with human population increases) and the short term programs were not considered a success by the authors of a shark culling study.<ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/handle/10125/2202|title=A Review of Shark Control in Hawaii with Recommendations for Future Research|date=April 1994|first1=Bradley M.|last1=Wetherbee|first2=Christopher G.|last2=Lowe|first3=Gerald L.|last3=Crow|volume=48|issue=2|pages=95\u2013115|journal=Pacific Science}}</ref> The study concluded that the culls \"do not appear to have had measurable effects on the rate of shark attacks in Hawaiian waters\".\n\nThe publication came at a time during intense community debate over culling in Hawaii, documented by local journalist Jim Borg in his 1993 book, ''Tigers of the Sea, Hawaii\u2019s Deadly Tiger Sharks''.<ref>(Mutual Publishing, {{ISBN|978-1566470483}})</ref>  Borg detailed the debates between the study's authors and other scientists who argued that the experiences of South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal Shark Board<ref>See footnote 35</ref> demonstrated the effectiveness of the culling.  The debate began with the November 1991 shark attack killing of Martha Morrell off Maui and embroiled the subsequently formed Hawaii Shark Task Force, Borg writes.\n\nStatistics from 2013 showed the number of shark attacks in Hawaii was spiking.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/12/131203-science-shark-attack-hawaii-maui-fisherman-surfer-tiger-australia-bite-ocean/|title=Maui Death Raises Questions About Spike in Hawaiian Shark Attacks|archivedate=8 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108154117/http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/12/131203-science-shark-attack-hawaii-maui-fisherman-surfer-tiger-australia-bite-ocean/|accessdate=5 January 2017|website=National Geographic|first=Brian|last=Handwerk|date=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\n[[File:Sign warning of shark attacks at Boa Viagem Beach in Recife, Brazil.jpg|thumb|243x243px|A sign warns of elevated shark attack risk at a beach in Recife, Brazil.]]\nDrumlines and [[Long line fishing|long lines]] have been used successfully in [[Recife]] in a long term program, where shark attacks have been reduced by around 97%.<ref name=HazinAfonso>{{Cite journal|title=A green strategy for shark attack mitigation off Recife, Brazil|first1=F. H. V.|last1=Hazin|first2=A. S.|last2=Afonso|date=28 November 2013|doi=10.1111/acv.12096|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=17|issue=4|pages=287|hdl=10400.1/11160}}</ref> Sharks are initially caught on baited drum lines. Once captured, the sharks (if found alive) are humanely handled and tagged.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burrell|first=Andrew|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/features/killing-threat-no-safe-bet/story-e6frg6z6-1226811564509#mm-premium|title=Killing threat no safe bet|newspaper=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> They are then relocated offshore and their movements are tracked. The project is known as the Shark Monitoring Program of Recife (SMPR). A report assessing the program's performance was published in 2013. It stated: \"Overall, the SMPR seems to be less detrimental than shark meshing strategies while clearly contributing for enhancing bather safety; thus, it may provide an effective, ecologically balanced tool for assisting in shark attack mitigation.\"<ref name=HazinAfonso/>\n\n=== R\u00e9union Island (France) ===\nThe prevalence of shark attacks at [[R\u00e9union]] Island\u2014there were 19 attacks between 2011 and 2016, including seven which were fatal\u2014prompted [[R\u00e9union]] island's government to carry out a range of systematic long term shark protection activities, including a shark cull, utilising [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|\"smart\" drumlines]] and longlines.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/shark-attacks-smart-drum-lines-fact-check/7030538|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=3 March 2016|archivedate=3 October 2016|title=Fact Check: Are smart drum lines just a PR exercise?|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003120953/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/shark-attacks-smart-drum-lines-fact-check/7030538}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/surfer-shark-attack-reunion-island-leaves-man-without-arm-foot-2409300|title=Surfer Shark Attack On Reunion Island Leaves Man Without Arm And Foot|date=30 August 2016|first=Alexandra|last=Suarez|website=IBT|archivedate=26 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126004528/http://www.ibtimes.com/surfer-shark-attack-reunion-island-leaves-man-without-arm-foot-2409300|url-status=live|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>  In the five years to August 2016, more than 170 sharks were killed as part of the cull.<ref>{{citation|url=http://ocean71.com/chapters/shark-reunion-innovative-solutions-global-interest/|title=Forbidden Ocean in R\u00e9union Island|date=9 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126001825/http://ocean71.com/chapters/shark-reunion-innovative-solutions-global-interest/|archivedate=26 November 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=6 January 2017|website=Ocean71 Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two shark-proof fences were strung at beaches to the west of the island, at a cost of \u20ac2&nbsp;million. Maintenance of the fences is projected to cost \u20ac1&nbsp;million a year.<ref name=Schuetze>{{citation|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/why-this-indian-ocean-island-hot-spot-shark-attacks-180957498/#6P9FR3Ey7MtZeZUk.99|title=Why Is This Indian Ocean Island a Hot Spot for Shark Attacks?|website=Smithsonian.com|first=Christopher F.|last=Schuetze|date=14 December 2015|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> The protective nets / shark enclosures at the two beaches have a total length of just under 1 mile and are subject to damage from heavy swell. On 27 August 2016 a surfer lost an arm and a foot from a shark attack while surfing within one of the enclosures. It was reported that at the time of the attack there was a two-meter hole in the nets, most probably caused by the swell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magicseaweed.com/news/shark-attack-number-19-and-all-is-not-well-at-reunion-island/9420/|title=Shark attack number 19 and all is not well on Reunion Island|website=Magicseaweed|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003711/http://magicseaweed.com/news/shark-attack-number-19-and-all-is-not-well-at-reunion-island/9420/|date=2 September 2016|url-status=live|first=Craig|last=Jarvis|archivedate=26 November 2016|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{portalbar|Sharks}}\n\n[[Category:Shark attack prevention]]\n[[Category:Safety practices]]\n", "text_old": "There are a range of '''shark attack prevention''' techniques employed to reduce the risk of [[shark attack]] and keep people safe. They include removing sharks by various fishing methods, separating people and sharks, as well as observation, education and various technology-based solutions.\n\nTechniques that involve [[shark culling|culling sharks]] are contentious.  Environmental groups have voiced concern over the impact of reduced shark numbers on ocean ecosystems and the problem of by-catch of other marine life, particularly endangered species.<ref name=\"ausmarine\"/><ref name=\"SSQld\"/><ref name=\"Theguardian1\"/><ref name=\"Meyer\"/><ref name=\"Schetzer\"/> Because sharks are important to the ecosystem, killing them harms the ecosystem.<ref name=\"cullconserve\"/><ref>https://eu.oceana.org/en/importance-sharks Eu.oceana.org. ''The Importance of Sharks in the Ecosystem.'' Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Schetzer\"/>\n\n==Nets==\n\n===Shark net===\n\n{{Main|Shark net}}\n\nThe majority of [[shark net]]s used are [[Gillnetting|gillnets]], which is a wall of netting that hangs in the water and captures the targeted sharks by entanglement.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/interactions/gear/gillnet.htm|title=Gillnets: Fishing Gear and Risks to Protected Species|accessdate=6 January 2017|archivedate=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101002810/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/interactions/gear/gillnet.htm|publisher=United States Government|author=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|url-status=live|date=18 February 2014}}</ref> The nets may be as much as {{convert|186|m|ft}} long, set at a depth of {{convert|6|m|ft}}, have a mesh size of {{convert|500|mm|in}} and are designed to catch sharks longer than {{convert|2|m|ft}} in length.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/fisheries/services/shark-control-program/shark-control-equipment-and-locations|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|title=Shark control equipment and locations|archivedate=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101091020/https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/fisheries/services/shark-control-program/shark-control-equipment-and-locations|publisher=Queensland Government|author=Department of Agriculture and Fisheries|date=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nShark nets do not offer complete protection but work on the principle of \"fewer sharks, fewer attacks\". They reduce occurrence via shark mortality. Shark nets such as those in [[New South Wales]] are designed to entangle and kill sharks and other animals that pass near them.<ref name=\"sealife\"/> Historical shark attack figures suggest that the use of shark nets does markedly reduce the incidence of shark attack when implemented on a regular and consistent basis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880|title=Can governments protect people from killer sharks?|website=ABC News|date=22 December 2013|url-status=live|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=5 January 2017|archivedate=31 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031175236/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880}}</ref><ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref name =\"Dudley\"/><ref name=\"SAJS\" />\n\nA downside with shark nets is that they do result in [[bycatch]], including threatened and endangered species.<ref name=\"cullconserve\">{{citation|url=https://briantissot.com/2015/08/20/shark-attacks-and-the-surfers-dilemma-cull-or-conserve/|date=20 August 2015|title=Shark Attacks and the Surfer's Dilemma: Cull or Conserve|last=Tissot|first=Brian|url-status=live|accessdate=5 January 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122154405/https://briantissot.com/2015/08/20/shark-attacks-and-the-surfers-dilemma-cull-or-conserve/|archivedate=22 November 2016|website=Dr Abalone}}</ref> Between September 2017 and April 2018, 403 animals were killed in the nets in [[New South Wales]], including 10 critically endangered [[grey nurse shark]]s, 7 [[dolphin]]s, 7 [[green turtle]]s and 14 [[great white shark]]s.<ref name=\"swellnet\">http://www.swellnet.com/news/swellnet-dispatch/2018/08/04/sydney-shark-nets-set-stay-despite-drumline-success Swellnet.com. ''Sydney shark nets set to stay despite drumline success.'' Bruce Mackenzie. August 4, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> However note that [[bycatch]] from shark nets is minor compared to bycatch from commercial fishing<ref name=\"theherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|title=Beyond the panic: the facts about shark nets|first=Australian Community Media - Fairfax|last=Media|date=8 November 2016|publisher=|accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Bett\">{{cite journal |last1=Stephanie M. Bettis |title=Shark Bycatch in Commercial Fisheries: A Global Perspective |journal=Nova Southeastern University |date=July 2017 |url=https://nsuworks.nova.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com.au/&httpsredir=1&article=1331&context=cnso_stucap |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref> with estimates of 50 million sharks caught unintentionally each year.<ref name=\"Sharksav\">{{cite web |title=Shark fin trade myths and truths |url=http://www.sharksavers.org/files/8613/3185/9956/Shark_Bycatch_FACT_SHEET_Shark_Savers.pdf |website=Sharksavers |accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nTotal cost for the shark netting program in [[New South Wales]] for the 2009/10 year was approximately {{AUD|1 million}}, which included the cost of the nets, contractors, observers and shark technicians, shark meshing equipment (dolphin pingers and whale alarms etc.), and compliance audit activities.<ref name=\"NSWGOV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/623400/Report-into-the-NSW-Shark-Meshing-Program.pdf |title=Report into the NSW Shark Meshing (Bather Protection) Program |author=Green, M., Ganassin, C. and Reid, D. D. |publisher=State of New South Wales through NSW Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> For the 51 beaches protected,<ref name=\"NSWGOV\"/> this represents a financial cost of approximately {{AUD|20,000}} per beach per year.\n\nShark nets have been criticized by environmentalists and conservationists; they say shark nets damage the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"sealife\">http://www.sealifetrust.org.au/news/latest/shark-nets-australia-work ''Shark nets in Australia \u2013 what are they and how do they work?'' Sealifetrust.org.au. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"sharkangels\">http://www.sharkangels.org/index.php/media/news/157-shark-nets ''Shark Nets.'' Sharkangels.org. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"cullconserve\"/> The current net program in New South Wales has been described as being \"extremely destructive\" to marine life;<ref>https://www.buzzfeed.com/elfyscott/heres-what-you-need-to-know-about-australias-smart-drum ''Here's What You Need To Know About Australia's SMART Drum Lines Being Used To Prevent Shark Attacks.'' Elfy Scott. July 5, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> it has also been called \"outdated and ineffective\".<ref name=\"swellnet\"/>  The New South Wales government prohibits people from rescuing entangled animals \u2014 this prohibition has been called \"heartless and cruel\".<ref>https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/nsw/2018/01/09/greens-shark-nets-rays/ ''Threat to cut shark nets if government fails to act.'' Rachel Eddie. January 9, 2018. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Shark barrier===\n[[File:Coogee Beach gnangarra-215.jpg|thumb|[[Coogee, Western Australia|Coogee Beach]] shark barrier floats and jetty]]\n\n{{Main|Shark barrier}}\n\nA [[shark barrier]] (otherwise known as a \"shark-proof enclosure\" or \"beach enclosure\") is seabed-to-surface protective barrier that is placed around a beach to separate people from sharks. Shark barriers form a fully enclosed swimming area that prevents sharks from entering.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news|last=Meerman|first=Ruben|title=Shark nets |website=ABC Science|date=16 January 2009|url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2002/03/07/2116717.htm|accessdate=5 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129034201/http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2002/03/07/2116717.htm|archivedate=29 November 2016}}</ref> Shark barrier design has evolved from rudimentary fencing materials to netted structures held in place with buoys and anchors. Recent designs have used plastics to increase strength and versatility.\n\nWhen deployed in sheltered areas shark barriers offer complete protection and are seen as a more environmentally friendly option as they largely avoid bycatch. However barriers are not effective on surf beaches because they usually disintegrate in the swell and so are normally constructed only around sheltered areas such as harbour beaches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/fact-file-protecting-people-from-shark-attacks/5164882|date=5 January 2015|title=Fact File: Protecting people from shark attacks|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nA [[Middleton Beach shark barrier|shark barrier installed at Middleton beach]] in [[Albany, Western Australia]] cost {{AUD|340,000}} to install, with annual maintenance budgeted at {{AUD|30,000}} per annum.<ref name=ABC1>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-16/albany-council-awards-shark-barrier-contract/7033664|title=Albany shark barrier contract goes to Australian firm|date=16 December 2015|accessdate=28 December 2016|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref> On [[R\u00e9union]] Island in 2015 two shark proof enclosures cost \u20ac2&nbsp;million to install and \u20ac1&nbsp;million a year to maintain.<ref name=Schuetze/>\n\n==Drum lines==\n{{Main|Drum line (shark control)}}\nA [[Drum line (shark control)|drum line]] is an unmanned aquatic trap used to lure and capture large sharks using baited hooks. They are typically deployed near popular swimming beaches with the intention of reducing the number of sharks in the vicinity and therefore the probability of shark attack. Drum lines were first deployed to protect users of the marine environment from sharks in [[Queensland]], Australia in 1962. During this time, they were just as successful in reducing the frequency of shark attacks as the shark nets.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www2.dpi.qld.gov.au/extra/pdf/fishweb/sharksafetyreport.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140123173415/http://www2.dpi.qld.gov.au/extra/pdf/fishweb/sharksafetyreport.pdf|archivedate=23 January 2014|accessdate=6 January 2017|title=A Report on the Queensland Shark Safety Program|date=March 2006|publisher=Queensland Government|author=Department of Primary Industries and Fisheries|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref name =\"Dudley\">{{cite journal|last1=Dudley, S.F.J.|title=A comparison of the shark control programs of New South Wales and Queensland (Australia) and KwaZulu-Natal (South Africa)|journal=Ocean Coast Manag|volume=34|date=1997|issue=34|pages=1\u201327|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/223563025|doi=10.1016/S0964-5691(96)00061-0}}</ref> More recently, drumlines have also been used with great success in [[Recife]], Brazil where the number of attacks has been shown to have reduced by 97% when the drumlines are deployed.<ref name=HazinAfonso/> While shark nets and drum lines share the same purpose, drum lines are more effective at targeting the three sharks that are considered most dangerous to swimmers: the [[bull shark]], [[tiger shark]] and [[great white shark]].<ref name=Dudleyetal>{{cite journal |first1=Sheldon F.J.|last1=Dudley|first2=R.C.|last2=Haestier |last3=Cox|first3=K.R.|first4=M.|last4= Murray |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MF98026.pdf |title=Shark control: Experimental fishing with baited drumlines |accessdate=22 January 2010|journal=Marine and Freshwater Research|volume=49|issue=7|date=January 1998}}</ref> [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]]s can also be utilised to move sharks, which greatly reduces mortality of sharks and [[bycatch]] to less than 2%.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\" />\n\nIn 2014 a three-month trial utilising up to 60 drum lines in [[Western Australia]] cost {{AUD|1.28 million}}.<ref name=\"WA-cost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.dpc.wa.gov.au/Publications/Documents/Review%20-%20Western%20Australia%20Shark%20Hazard%20Mitigation%20Drum%20Line%20Program%202013-14.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102171105/https://www.dpc.wa.gov.au/Publications/Documents/Review%20-%20Western%20Australia%20Shark%20Hazard%20Mitigation%20Drum%20Line%20Program%202013-14.pdf|archivedate=2 January 2017|title=Review: Western Australia Shark Hazard Mitigation Drum Line Program 2013/14|publisher=Government of Western Australia|author=Department of the Premier and Cabinet |accessdate=3 January 2017|date=June 2014}}</ref>\n\nDrum line programmes that involve [[culling]] have been criticized for being environmentally destructive and [[speciesism|speciesist]], and have sparked public demonstrations and vocal opposition, particularly from environmentalists, animal welfare advocates and ocean activists.<ref name=\"ausmarine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausmarinescience.com/marine-science-basics/marine-biology/sharks/|title=Sharks|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SSQld\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seashepherd.org.au/apex-harmony/overview/queensland.html|title=Queensland - Overview|website=www.seashepherd.org.au|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Theguardian1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/feb/12/was-serious-threat-shark-policy-condemned-by-senate|title=Western Australia's 'serious threat' shark policy condemned by Senate|first=Calla|last=Wahlquist|date=12 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"Meyer\">{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/western-australias-shark-culls-lack-bite-and-science-21371|title=Western Australia's shark culls lack bite (and science)|first=Carl|last=Meyer|publisher=|accessdate=22 April 2017}}</ref> Conservationists say killing sharks on drum lines harms the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"Schetzer\">Alana Schetzer (8 May 2017). http://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/sharks-how-a-cull-could-ruin-an-ecosystem ''\"Sharks: How a cull could ruin an ecosystem\".'' Science Matters. University of Melbourne \u2013 via Pursuit. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> In 2018, endangered [[hammerhead shark]]s were found dead on Queensland's drum lines.<ref name=\"ntd\"/> The current drum line program in [[Queensland]] has been called \"outdated, cruel and ineffective\".<ref name=\"ntd\">https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ ''Endangered Hammerhead Sharks Dead on Drum Line in Great Barrier Reef.'' Jack Phillips. Ntd.tv. Retrieved September 20, 2018.</ref> However environmental damage from drumlines is minor compared to commercial fishing<ref name=\"theherald\" /><ref name=\"Bett\" /> with estimates of 50 million sharks caught unintentionally each year.<ref name=\"Sharksav\" />\n\n==Other protection methods==\n[[File:Living in a shark-eat-shark world 150617-M-RT812-001.jpg|thumb|A sign at Pyramid Rock Beach in [[Hawaii]] warning about a shark sighting, 2015]]\n\n===Moving sharks===\nMoving sharks is a way of reducing shark attacks and reducing shark mortality, by capturing,  transporting and releasing the sharks further shore. In Recife, Brazil, sharks that were near shore were captured and physically moved offshore with 70% of potentially aggressive sharks and 78% of other animals caught released alive.<ref name=\"HazinAfonso\" /> Sharks that were moved did not return to the same location.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.yahoo.com/tv/shark-week-science-empathy-meet-shark-storm-shark-exile-172736463.html | title=Shark Week: Science and Empathy Meet in 'Shark Storm' and 'Shark Exile'}}</ref> This technique has also been successfully demonstrated in the NSW North Coast [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]] trial (Australia) where 99% of targeted sharks and 98% of other animals caught were released alive.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\">{{cite web |title=NSW North Coast SMART drumline data |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/fishing/sharks/management/smart-drumlines |website=NSW Government: Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe West Australian Government are now trialling the same technique along [[Western Australia]]'s South West coast, near [[Gracetown]].<ref name=\"WA_Smart_trial\">{{cite web |title=SCIENTIFIC NON-LETHAL SMART DRUMLINE TRIAL |url=https://www.sharksmart.com.au/research/smart-drumline-trial/ |website=Sharksmart |publisher=Government of West Australia |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sharks to be caught on SMART drum lines off WA's South West after Labor U-turn |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-14/shark-attacks-prompt-wa-to-conduct-smart-drum-line-trial/10117230 |accessdate=14 August 2018 |agency=ABC News |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Shark tagging and tracking===\nAcross the world a sample of sharks have been tagged with electronic devices that transmit their location.<ref name=\"Tracking\">{{cite web|title=Tracking sharks|url=http://www.trackingsharks.com/track-sharks/|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>  Acoustic tags transmit pulses which are detected by underwater listening stations when the sharks swim close by, typically within 500 metres.<ref name=\"WA_monitor\"/><ref name=\"Options\"/> Fin-mounted satellite tags are also commonly used.<ref name=\"Options\"/> These tags allow shark movements and behaviour to be monitored and studied and swimmers and surfers can be warned if a shark is detected close to shore.<ref name=\"WA_monitor\">{{cite web|title=Shark monitoring network|url=http://sharksmart.com.au/research/shark-monitoring-network/|website=Sharksmart|publisher=West Australian Government|accessdate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHowever a limitation with the system is the tagging will only highlight a very small portion of the dangerous sharks present.<ref name=\"Options\"/> It also may lead people into a false sense of security.<ref name=\"Options\"/>\n\n===Shark spotting===\nShark-spotting programs using drones, fixed wing aircraft, helicopters, [[beach patrol]]s, observation towers and even blimps, are being used and trialled in various locations across the globe.<ref name=\"Options\">{{cite news|last1=Turnbull|first1=Samantha|title=Protecting humans from sharks: What are the options?|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-11-01/protecting-humans-from-sharks-what-are-the-options/7979206|accessdate=28 May 2017|publisher=ABC News|date=3 November 2016}}</ref> However visibility issues with water clarity can be a problem particularly with aerial patrols, which have been found to identify less than 20% of sharks present.<ref name=\"NSWGOV\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Robbins, William D. |display-authors=etal |title=Experimental evaluation of shark detection rates by aerial observers|journal=PLoS ONE |volume=9 |issue=2|date=2014|page=e83456|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0083456|pmid=24498258|pmc=3911894}}</ref>  There is also the financial cost of hiring aircraft and/or personnel to conduct the surveillance.<ref name=\"Options\"/>\n\n=== Shark sonar ===\nIn September 2015, a shark sonar created by [[Ric Richardson]] was tested in [[Byron Bay, New South Wales|Byron Bay]], Australia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian first: sonar shark detection trial in Byron Bay|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/shark-sonar-trial-may-help-with-early-warning-for-/2779966/|website=Northern Star}}</ref> It is a passive sonar device that does not interfere with animals like dolphins. The final device will sit on the ocean floor and can detect sharks over 2,5 meters long when they are 100 meters away. An alarm will notify people that they have to go out of the water. Other shark sonar systems are also been tested and showing promising results.<ref>{{cite web |title=Evaluation of Clever Buoy Shark Detection System |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0007/815866/evaluation-of-clever-buoy-shark-detection-system-summary.pdf |website=New South Wales Department of Primary Industries |accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Personal shark repellents ===\n\n{{Main|Shark repellant}}\n\nA shark repellent is any method of driving [[shark]]s away from an area and includes [[magnetic shark repellent]], [[electropositive shark repellent]]s, electrical repellents (including [[Shark Shield]]) and [[semiochemical]]s. One example is a product called Anti-Shark 100<ref name=\"Shark_tec\">{{cite web|title=Anti-Shark 100 Product Overview|url=https://www.sharktecdefense.com|website=SharkTec|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref> which is an aerosol can that contains an extract of dead shark tissue. There is a range of evidence that supports the effectiveness of this product.<ref name=\"Life_hacker\">{{cite web|last1=Francis|first1=Hannah|title=Do Shark Repellents Actually Work?|url=https://www.lifehacker.com.au/2016/01/do-shark-repellents-actually-work/|website=Lifehacker|accessdate=5 June 2017|date=2016-01-04}}</ref> Chemical repellents have been researched since before the 1940s, some of which have raised concerns as to their effectiveness. The semiochemical used in the Anti-shark 100 product have been independently tested & verified on Caribbean reef sharks, however there are concerns it may attract Tiger and White sharks.<ref name =\"NSW\">{{cite journal|last1=Cardno|title=Shark Deterrents and Detectors: Review of Bather Protection Technologies|journal=Prepared for NSW Department of Primary Industries|date=October 2015|pages=12|url=http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/578999/cardno-review-of-bather-protection-technologies.pdf|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOther examples of personal shark protection technologies include wearing interruption patterned or camouflage wetsuits,<ref>{{cite news|last=Starr|first=Michelle |url=http://www.cnet.com.au/aussies-design-shark-proof-wetsuits-339344936.htm |title=Aussies design shark-proof wetsuits|website=C-Net|location=Australia |date=22 July 2013|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> magnetic repellents incorporating a small magnet in a band worn on the wrist or ankle,<ref name=\"Life_hacker\"/> acoustic repellents that mimic the sound of [[orcas]]<ref name=\"Choice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.choice.com.au/health-and-body/diet-and-fitness/surfing-and-snowboarding/articles/shark-repellents-review|title=Under attack: Do shark repellents work?|last1=Doyle|first1=Chris|date=2016-10-03|website=Choice|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> and changing surf board colours.<ref name=\"Options\"/> However none of the products associated with these technologies have been independently tested.<ref name=\"Choice\"/><ref name=\"Options\"/><ref name=\"Life_hacker\"/>\n\n====Shark shield====\n\n{{Main|Shark Shield}}\n\nShark Shield is a personal electronic device that creates an [[Electro magnetic field|electromagnetic field]] to deter [[shark attack]]s and is used by [[Surfing|surfers]], [[scuba diver]]s, [[spearfishing]], and ocean [[kayak fishing]]. It has been considered one of the few electrical devices on the market that has performed independent trials to determine the effectiveness <ref name=\"Kempster\">{{cite journal|display-authors=etal|vauthors=Kempster RM, Egeberg CA, Hart NS, Ryan L, Chapuis L, Kerr CC|date=1 June 2016|title=How Close is too Close? The Effect of a Non-Lethal Electric Shark Deterrent on White Shark Behaviour|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=11|issue=7|page=e0157717|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0157717|pmc=4930202|pmid=27368059}}</ref><ref name=\"Huveneers\">{{citation|last=Huveneers|first=C.|title=Effects of the Shark Shield electric deterrent on the behaviour of white sharks Carcharodon carcharias|date=June 2012|url=http://www.sardi.sa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/173876/Risk_Assessment_of_the_Shark_Shield_Report_-_FINAL_19_06_2012.pdf|location=Australia|publisher=SARDI|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> at deterring shark attacks.<ref name=\"Choice\" />  However note that the Shark Shield does not work in all situations<ref name=\"Kempster\" /><ref name=\"ABC_sa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2012/06/20/3529306.htm|title=SA researchers trial effectiveness of electronic shark deterrent devices on Great Whites|last1=Williamson|first1=Brett|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=1 June 2017|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Huveneers\" /> and divers have been attacked whilst wearing Shark Shield.<ref name=\"Choice\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portlincolntimes.com.au/story/1608925/clarkson-was-wearing-shark-shield/|title=Clarkson was wearing shark shield|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=2 June 2017|publisher=Port Lincoln Times}}</ref>\n\nThe West Australian government has also announced that they are supporting the Shark Shield FREEDOM 7 and the Ocean Guardian FREEDOM+ Surf via a $200 subsidiary.<ref name=\"Sharksmart_faq\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sharksmart.com.au/staying-safe/rebate-faqs/|title=SHARK DETERRENT REBATE - FAQ|website=Sharksmart|publisher=West Australian Government|accessdate=31 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Protection by dolphins ===\nThere are documented instances of [[bottlenose dolphin]]s protecting humans from shark attacks, one off the coast of [[New Zealand]] in 2004<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4034383.stm | work=BBC News | title=Dolphins prevent NZ shark attack | date=23 November 2004 | accessdate=6 April 2010 | first=Phil | last=Mercer}}</ref> and one attack on a surfer in northern [[California]] in August 2007.<ref name=\"msnbc1\">{{cite web|last=Celizic |first=Mike |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21689083/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109080539/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21689083/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 November 2007 |title=Dolphins rescue surfer from shark - TODAY People - People: Tales of survival - TODAYshow.com |publisher=MSNBC |date=8 November 2007 |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> There is no accepted explanation for this behavior; as mentioned in the ''Journal of Zoology'', \"The importance of interactions between sharks and cetaceans has been a subject of much conjecture, but few studies have addressed these interactions\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Predator\u2013prey and competitive interactions between sharks (order Selachii) and dolphins (suborder Odontoceti): a review |doi=10.1017/S0952836901000061 |volume=253 |journal=Journal of Zoology |pages=53\u201368|year = 2001|last1 = Heithaus|first1 = Michael R.|citeseerx=10.1.1.404.130 }}</ref> In some cases, sharks have been seen attacking, or trying to attack dolphins.<ref>http://www.abcactionnews.com/news/local/story/Rehabilitated-dolphin-dies-after-shark-attack/Os5uEUUiFU2NukbdnqiZXQ.cspx</ref>  The presence of porpoises does not indicate the absence of sharks as both eat the same food<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncseagrant.org/home/coastwatch/coastwatch-articles?task=showArticle&id=570 |title=North Carolina Sea Grant \u2013 Coastwatch Articles |publisher=Ncseagrant.org |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> and surfers have been attacked by sharks whilst in the presence of dolphins.<ref>{{cite news|last1=PerthNow|title=Bunbury man tells of close encounter with shark|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/western-australia/bunbury-man-tells-of-close-encounter-with-shark/news-story/7e58f37ba2c46f969a6af4357b0fd8b9|accessdate=20 June 2017|newspaper=Sunday Times|date=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== By country ==\n=== Australia ===\n==== Queensland and New South Wales ====\n[[File:Graph of sharks caught in Queensland's Shark Control Program (by type) July 1997- June 2014.PNG|thumb|Graph of sharks caught in Queensland's shark control program (by type) July 1997- June 2014]]\n\nIn Queensland and NSW systematic long term shark control programs using shark nets and drumlines are utilised to reduce the risk of shark attack. Since 1936 sharks nets have been utilised off Sydney beaches.<ref name=\"Coastwatch-article\">{{cite web |url=http://52.64.240.87/environment/20632/nick-carroll-on-beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets |title=Nick Carroll On-Beyond the Panic, The Facts about Shark Nets |last=Carroll|first= Nick |publisher=Coastal Watch |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> Nowadays they are employed on both NSW and Queensland beaches; 83 beaches are meshed in Queensland compared with NSW's current 51.<ref name=\"Coastwatch-article\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|date=8 November 2016|newspaper=Newcastle Herald|title=Nick Carroll: the facts about shark nets|accessdate=5 January 2017|publisher=Fairfax Media|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112082645/http://www.theherald.com.au/story/4275374/beyond-the-panic-the-facts-about-shark-nets/|archivedate=12 November 2016|url-status=live|first=Nick|last=Carroll}}</ref>\n\nThe technique of setting drum lines is also used in Queensland and New South Wales, where they have been used in association with shark nets. Before 1962, there were 82 recorded attacks. Since the policy was implemented there has only been one recorded death, at [[Amity Point, Queensland|Amity Point]] in January 2006. 21-year-old Sarah Kate Whiley was attacked by as many as three sharks in Rainbow Channel. The attack occurred in an unpatrolled area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-01-09/lifesavers-warn-swimmers-off-amity-point/775902 |title=Lifesavers warn swimmers off Amity Point|website=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 January 2006|archivedate=28 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028145649/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-01-09/lifesavers-warn-swimmers-off-amity-point/775902|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Queensland Fisheries Minister [[John McVeigh (politician)|John McVeigh]] has described the longevity of the netting and drum line program as being \"a good indicator that it had the support of most Queenslanders\".<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|last=King|first=Rihanna|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/21017928// |title=Drum lines 'keep State safe'|newspaper=The West Australian|date=25 January 2014|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe baited drum lines attract sharks from within a 3&ndash;5&nbsp;km radius, preventing sharks from reaching swimming areas. They also capture less bycatch than shark nets.<ref name=Dudleyetal/>\n\nThere were a total of 97 fatalities attributed to shark attacks in Queensland between 1858 and 2014. In New South Wales there were a total of 96 fatalities attributed to shark attack between 1771 and 2014.\n\nThe current shark-killing programs in Queensland and New South Wales have been called [[shark culling|culls]], and have been criticized by environmentalists, who say killing sharks harms the marine ecosystem.<ref name=\"marineconservation\"/><ref name=\"ntd\"/> Between 1950 and 2008, 577 great white sharks and 352 tiger sharks were killed in the nets in New South Wales \u2014 also during this period, 15,135 marine animals were caught and killed in the nets, including whales, turtles, rays, dolphins, and dugongs.<ref name=\"marineconservation\">https://web.archive.org/web/20181002102324/https://www.marineconservation.org.au/pages/shark-culling.html Marineconservation.org.au. Shark culling (archived). Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref> In Queensland, from 2001 to 2018, a total of 10,480 sharks were killed on lethal drum lines.<ref>https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/queensland-government-kills-sharks-faces-court-challenge Queensland Government Kills Sharks, Faces Court Challenge. maritime-executive.com. September 4, 2018. [https://web.archive.org/web/20180904151759/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/queensland-government-kills-sharks-faces-court-challenge archived] from the original on 2018-09-04. Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref>\n\n===== NSW North Coast shark net and smart drumline trial =====\n\nFollowing 11 shark attacks along the NSW north coast between 2014 and 2016, including two fatalities,<ref>{{cite news|title=Episode 1: The Anger|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/state-politics/ballina-lennox-byron-shark-crisis/news-story/70abd956652869c53a7d1d464ce971c6|accessdate=23 March 2018|newspaper=The Australian|date=5 December 2016}}</ref> [[Shark nets]] and [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumlines]] were deployed in December 2016 to cover five additional beaches along the NSW North Coast in a two-year trial. Five nets were deployed off Seven Mile Beach off Lennox Head; Sharpes, Shelly and Lighthouse beaches off Ballina; and Main Beach at Evans Head.<ref name=\"NCSN_Trial\">{{cite web|title=North Coast Shark Net Trial: Summary|url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/fishing/sharks/management/shark-net-trial|website=NSW Department of Primary Industry|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> Twenty five drumlines were also deployed among nets at Ballina and Evans Head beaches (15 off Ballina; 10 off Evans Head).<ref name=\"NCSN_Trial\" /> The trial was successful with no shark attacks occurring at the protected beaches.<ref name=\"FAQ\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Shark nets will return to NSW's north coast beaches|url=https://www.tweeddailynews.com.au/news/shark-nets-will-return-nsws-north-coast-beaches/3218840/|accessdate=23 March 2018|publisher=Tweed Daily News|date=1 September 2017}}</ref> The [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|SMART drumline]] caught 230 targeted sharks with 99% of targeted sharks and 98% of other animals caught were released alive.<ref name=\"NSW_Smart_Drumlines\"/> The SMART drumlines are now being expanded to other NSW regions.<ref name=\"FAQ\">{{cite web |title=SMART Drumlines: Frequently asked Questions |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/732624/SMART-drumlines-faqs.pdf |website=NSW Department of Primary Industries |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref> The shark net trial caught 11 targeted sharks and had a 54% survival rate for all animals caught and will not be continued.<ref name=\"NSW_Trial_Final\">{{cite journal |last1=NSW Department of Primary Industries |title=Second NSW north coast shark-meshing trial Final Report |date=August 2018 |url=https://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/829458/second-north-coast-shark-meshing-final-report.pdf |accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Western Australia ====\n[[File:Albany Shark barrier.JPG|thumb|[[Middleton Beach shark barrier]], [[Albany, Western Australia]]]]\n{{Main|Western Australian shark cull}}\nIn August 2018 following continual shark attacks and public pressure the West Australian state government announced a 12-month trial of [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|\"smart\" drumlines]] along [[Western Australia]]'s South West coast, near [[Gracetown]].<ref name=\"WA_trial\" >{{cite news |title=Sharks to be caught on SMART drum lines off WA's South West after Labor U-turn |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-14/shark-attacks-prompt-wa-to-conduct-smart-drum-line-trial/10117230 |accessdate=14 August 2018 |publisher=ABC News |date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nWestern Australia also deploys shark enclosures in a range of locations<ref>{{citation|title=Shark attacks in Australia: a timeline|publisher=Australian Geographic|date=2014|url= http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/topics/scienceenvironment/2014/01/shark-attacks-in-australia-a-timeline/|accessdate= 7 January 2015}}</ref> as well as aerial shark spotters, beach patrols, shark tagging efforts and associated tracking and notification systems.\n\nThere were a total of 114 unprovoked shark attacks in West Australia between 1870 and 2016,<ref>[http://www.sharkattackfile.net/incidentlog.htm Global shark attack file > Incident Log] ''SharkAttackFile.net'' Accessed 2018-08-14</ref> including 16 fatalities since 2000.<ref name=Aust>{{cite news |last1=Carmody |first1=James |title=Fatal shark attack near Esperance off WA's south-east coast claims diver's life |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-05/shark-attack-reported-near-esperance-off-wa-south-east-coast/11842420 |accessdate=5 January 2020 |publisher=ABC News |date=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== South Australia ====\nIn [[South Australia]], spotter planes and a small number of patrolled swimming beaches are the only methods used to mitigate the risk of shark attack. On 6 February 2014, Port Lincoln tuna \"[[Business magnate|baron]]\" [[Hagen Stehr]] expressed his support for the [[Western Australian shark cull]]. He also stated that his business' spotter planes had observed increases in great white shark numbers off the west coast of [[Eyre Peninsula]]. He acknowledged that his tuna farming operations attract some sharks. He told ''[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]'' that he believed \"selected culling of sharks is a must. It is crazy stuff to put them under protection so it becomes a major offence to kill them.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Austin|first=Nigel |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/port-lincoln-tuna-baron-hagen-stehr-says-shark-culling-is-a-must/story-fni6uo1m-1226820051425|title=Port Lincoln tuna baron Hagen Stehr says shark culling is a must|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|location= South Australia |date=7 February 2014|accessdate=9 February 2014}}</ref> Critics of Stehr's stance note that a cull of sharks in SA would be beneficial to his business, as tuna is a major source of food for sharks. Shark attack survivor turned conservationist [[Rodney Fox]] has spoken out against the cull, saying \"When a shark attacks someone, we go 'the shark needs to be punished'. They don't live under our laws. It's a different world down there and it should be treated differently.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Dempster|first=Alice |url=http://www.victorharbortimes.com.au/story/2099778/rodney-fox-visits-victor-harbor/ |title=Rodney Fox visits Victor Harbor|newspaper=The Times|location=Victor Harbor, South Australia |date=19 February 2014|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt September 2014, there had been a total of 82 [[shark attacks in South Australia]] since 1836, including 20 fatalities.<ref>[http://www.sharkattackfile.net/incidentlog.htm Global shark attack file > Incident Log] ''SharkAttackFile.net'' Accessed 2014-02-09.</ref>\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[File:Shark spotting information sign, Noordhoek Beach, ZA.jpg|thumb|upright|Shark spotting information sign at ''Noordhoek'' Beach in [[South Africa]] (2015)]]\nIn [[KwaZulu-Natal]], South Africa a long term shark control program utilising a combination of shark nets and drum lines are used to mitigate the risk of shark attack. The region's shark attack statistics primarily reflect the effectiveness of netting, as drum lines were only introduced recently, following their successful use for over 40 years in Queensland, Australia. The [[KwaZulu-Natal Sharks Board]] (KZNSB) says \"Both types of equipment function by reducing shark numbers in the vicinity of protected beaches, thereby lowering the probability of encounters between sharks and people at those beaches.\" The KZNSB says, \"At [[Durban]], from 1943 until the installation of shark nets in 1952, there were seven fatal attacks. Since the installation of nets there have been no fatalities at Durban and no incidents resulting in serious injury.\" The KZNSB also says, \"At KwaZulu-Natal's other [netted] beaches, from 1940 until most of those beaches were first netted in the 1960s, there were 16 fatal attacks and 11 resulting in serious injury. In the three decades since nets were installed, there have been no fatal attacks at those beaches and only four resulting in serious injury.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shark.co.za/SharkNetsMore|title=Shark Nets, Drum Lines & Safe Swimming|author=KwaZulu-Natal Shark Board|location=South Africa|accessdate=3 February 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128015833/http://www.shark.co.za/SharkNetsMore|archivedate=28 January 2014}}</ref> The presence of nets has greatly reduced the number of shark attacks along Natal beaches.<ref name=\"SAJS\">{{cite journal |title=Shark attacks on the South African coast between 1960 and 1990 |journal=South African Journal of Science |date=October 1991 |volume=87 |issue=10 |pages=513\u2013518 |url=https://journals.co.za/content/sajsci/87/10/AJA00382353_7199 |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> It is unclear whether more sharks caught on drum lines survive when compared to shark net captures in KwaZulu-Natal, but the lines have shown reduced non-target species bycatch. Drum lines set in the region are baited with 500 grams of meat per hook and are believed to only attract sharks from several hundred metres away.<ref>{{citation|last=Kearney|first=Alison|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~spea/pubs/undergrad-honors/volume-5/kearney_allison.pdf|title=Environmental Impacts of Shark Nets on the KwaZulu-Natal Coast|publisher=Indiana University|location=USA|date=2011}}</ref>\n\nSeasonal and temporary bathing bans and \"discretionary bathing\" are additional strategies employed in the region. Bans often follow net displacement or damage due to storms or swell, or net removal due to whale stranding. Nets are also removed during the annual [[sardine run]] to limit the degree of bycatch during the event. Pressure from the tourism industry to reinstate nets during the sardine run has previously proven \"disastrous\", resulting in large numbers of shark and dolphin mortalities.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe \"shark control\" program in KwaZulu-Natal has been called \"archaic\" and \"disastrous to the ecosystem\" (by environmentalists).<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> In a 30-year period, more than 33,000 sharks have been killed in KwaZulu-Natal's shark-killing program \u2014 also during this period, 2,211 turtles, 8,448 rays, and 2,310 dolphins were killed.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> Environmental groups say KwaZulu-Natal's \"shark control\" program is unethical and harms the marine ecosystem.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/> Activists in Durban say that Durban's shark nets serve no purpose.<ref>Cole, Barbara (August 3, 2018). https://www.iol.co.za/dailynews/news/durban-activists-claim-shark-nets-serve-no-purpose-16389703 \"Durban activists claim 'shark nets serve no purpose\". iol.co.za.  Retrieved November 30, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== USA ===\nIn [[Hawaii]], seven short term shark culls utilising [[Long line fishing|long-lines]] took place between 1959 and 1976. <ref name =\"Curtis-2012\">{{cite web |url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260382789_Responding_to_the_risk_of_white_shark_attack_Updated_statistics_prevention_control_methods_and_recommendations |title=Responding to the risk of white shark attack: updated statistics, prevention, control, methods and recommendation.  Chapter 29 In: M. L. Domeier (ed). Global Perspectives on the Biology and Life History of the White Shark |author=Curtis |display-authors=etal |date=2012|publisher=CRC Press. Boca Raton, FL. |accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> During this time, 4,668 sharks were caught, at a cost of US$300,000. Although the Hawaiian resident and tourist human population increased dramatically, the number of shark attacks remained constant (in contrast to [[Florida]], where the number of shark attacks has increased in line with human population increases) and the short term programs were not considered a success by the authors of a shark culling study.<ref name =\"Curtis-2012\"/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/handle/10125/2202|title=A Review of Shark Control in Hawaii with Recommendations for Future Research|date=April 1994|first1=Bradley M.|last1=Wetherbee|first2=Christopher G.|last2=Lowe|first3=Gerald L.|last3=Crow|volume=48|issue=2|pages=95\u2013115|journal=Pacific Science}}</ref> The study concluded that the culls \"do not appear to have had measurable effects on the rate of shark attacks in Hawaiian waters\".\n\nThe publication came at a time during intense community debate over culling in Hawaii, documented by local journalist Jim Borg in his 1993 book, ''Tigers of the Sea, Hawaii\u2019s Deadly Tiger Sharks''.<ref>(Mutual Publishing, {{ISBN|978-1566470483}})</ref>  Borg detailed the debates between the study's authors and other scientists who argued that the experiences of South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal Shark Board<ref>See footnote 35</ref> demonstrated the effectiveness of the culling.  The debate began with the November 1991 shark attack killing of Martha Morrell off Maui and embroiled the subsequently formed Hawaii Shark Task Force, Borg writes.\n\nStatistics from 2013 showed the number of shark attacks in Hawaii was spiking.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/12/131203-science-shark-attack-hawaii-maui-fisherman-surfer-tiger-australia-bite-ocean/|title=Maui Death Raises Questions About Spike in Hawaiian Shark Attacks|archivedate=8 November 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108154117/http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/12/131203-science-shark-attack-hawaii-maui-fisherman-surfer-tiger-australia-bite-ocean/|accessdate=5 January 2017|website=National Geographic|first=Brian|last=Handwerk|date=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\n[[File:Sign warning of shark attacks at Boa Viagem Beach in Recife, Brazil.jpg|thumb|243x243px|A sign warns of elevated shark attack risk at a beach in Recife, Brazil.]]\nDrumlines and [[Long line fishing|long lines]] have been used successfully in [[Recife]] in a long term program, where shark attacks have been reduced by around 97%.<ref name=HazinAfonso>{{Cite journal|title=A green strategy for shark attack mitigation off Recife, Brazil|first1=F. H. V.|last1=Hazin|first2=A. S.|last2=Afonso|date=28 November 2013|doi=10.1111/acv.12096|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=17|issue=4|pages=287|hdl=10400.1/11160}}</ref> Sharks are initially caught on baited drum lines. Once captured, the sharks (if found alive) are humanely handled and tagged.<ref>{{cite news|last=Burrell|first=Andrew|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/features/killing-threat-no-safe-bet/story-e6frg6z6-1226811564509#mm-premium|title=Killing threat no safe bet|newspaper=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> They are then relocated offshore and their movements are tracked. The project is known as the Shark Monitoring Program of Recife (SMPR). A report assessing the program's performance was published in 2013. It stated: \"Overall, the SMPR seems to be less detrimental than shark meshing strategies while clearly contributing for enhancing bather safety; thus, it may provide an effective, ecologically balanced tool for assisting in shark attack mitigation.\"<ref name=HazinAfonso/>\n\n=== R\u00e9union Island (France) ===\nThe prevalence of shark attacks at [[R\u00e9union]] Island\u2014there were 19 attacks between 2011 and 2016, including seven which were fatal\u2014prompted [[R\u00e9union]] island's government to carry out a range of systematic long term shark protection activities, including a shark cull, utilising [[Drum lines#Smart drumlines|\"smart\" drumlines]] and longlines.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/shark-attacks-smart-drum-lines-fact-check/7030538|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=3 March 2016|archivedate=3 October 2016|title=Fact Check: Are smart drum lines just a PR exercise?|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161003120953/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/shark-attacks-smart-drum-lines-fact-check/7030538}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/surfer-shark-attack-reunion-island-leaves-man-without-arm-foot-2409300|title=Surfer Shark Attack On Reunion Island Leaves Man Without Arm And Foot|date=30 August 2016|first=Alexandra|last=Suarez|website=IBT|archivedate=26 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126004528/http://www.ibtimes.com/surfer-shark-attack-reunion-island-leaves-man-without-arm-foot-2409300|url-status=live|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>  In the five years to August 2016, more than 170 sharks were killed as part of the cull.<ref>{{citation|url=http://ocean71.com/chapters/shark-reunion-innovative-solutions-global-interest/|title=Forbidden Ocean in R\u00e9union Island|date=9 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126001825/http://ocean71.com/chapters/shark-reunion-innovative-solutions-global-interest/|archivedate=26 November 2016|url-status=live|accessdate=6 January 2017|website=Ocean71 Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, two shark-proof fences were strung at beaches to the west of the island, at a cost of \u20ac2&nbsp;million. Maintenance of the fences is projected to cost \u20ac1&nbsp;million a year.<ref name=Schuetze>{{citation|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/why-this-indian-ocean-island-hot-spot-shark-attacks-180957498/#6P9FR3Ey7MtZeZUk.99|title=Why Is This Indian Ocean Island a Hot Spot for Shark Attacks?|website=Smithsonian.com|first=Christopher F.|last=Schuetze|date=14 December 2015|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> The protective nets / shark enclosures at the two beaches have a total length of just under 1 mile and are subject to damage from heavy swell. On 27 August 2016 a surfer lost an arm and a foot from a shark attack while surfing within one of the enclosures. It was reported that at the time of the attack there was a two-meter hole in the nets, most probably caused by the swell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://magicseaweed.com/news/shark-attack-number-19-and-all-is-not-well-at-reunion-island/9420/|title=Shark attack number 19 and all is not well on Reunion Island|website=Magicseaweed|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003711/http://magicseaweed.com/news/shark-attack-number-19-and-all-is-not-well-at-reunion-island/9420/|date=2 September 2016|url-status=live|first=Craig|last=Jarvis|archivedate=26 November 2016|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{portalbar|Sharks}}\n\n[[Category:Shark attack prevention]]\n[[Category:Safety practices]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDrum lines:Journal cites:, added 1 issue number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shark_attack_prevention"}
{"title_page": "Cerna, Tulcea", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Tulcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Tulcea County\n|subdivisions           = Cerna, General Praporgescu, Mircea Vod\u0103, Traian\n| name                    = Cerna\n| image_skyline           = Priopcea.jpg\n| image_caption           = The Priopcea Pass near Cerna village.\n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = Cerna jud Tulcea.png\n| coordinates             = {{coord|45|05|N|28|19|E|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| established_date        = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 221.65\n| leader_party            = PNL\n| leader_name             = Neculae Mu\u015fat\n| postal_code             =\n| website                 = [http://www.primariacerna.ro/ www.primariacerna.ro/] {{in lang|ro}}\n}}\n'''Cerna''' is a commune in [[Tulcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: Cerna ({{lang-bg|\u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430}}), General Praporgescu, Mircea Vod\u0103 (historical name: ''Acpunar'') and Traian.\n\n==Demographics==\nSituated in a hilly landscape 55 km from the city of Tulcea and 25 km from M\u0103cin, the village of Cerna had at the 2002 Romanian census a population of 2,427, and together with three smaller villages the population of the entire commune was 4,227. Estimates of the number of Megleno-Romanians in this village vary from 1,200 to 2,000. \n\nIn 1940, according to the stipulations of the [[Treaty of Craiova]], the Bulgarian population from Cerna was resettled to [[Southern Dobruja]], mainly to the village of Turcsmil, which was renamed [[Nova Cherna]] (New Cerna) in the memory of their former place of origin.\n\n==Notable natives==\n* [[Panait Cerna]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1155121}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cerna, Tulcea}}\n\n{{Tulcea County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Tulcea County]]\n\n{{Tulcea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Tulcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Tulcea County\n|subdivisions           = Cerna, General Praporgescu, Mircea Vod\u0103, Traian\n| name                    = Cerna\n| image_skyline           = Priopcea.jpg\n| image_caption           = The Priopcea Pass near Cerna village.\n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = Cerna jud Tulcea.png\n| coordinates             = {{coord|45|05|N|28|19|E|type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| established_date        = \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 221.65\n| leader_party            = [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]]\n| leader_name             = Neculae Mu\u015fat\n| postal_code             =\n| website                 = [http://www.primariacerna.ro/ www.primariacerna.ro/] {{in lang|ro}}\n}}\n'''Cerna''' is a commune in [[Tulcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of four villages: Cerna ({{lang-bg|\u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430}}), General Praporgescu, Mircea Vod\u0103 (historical name: ''Acpunar'') and Traian.\n\n==Demographics==\nSituated in a hilly landscape 55 km from the city of Tulcea and 25 km from M\u0103cin, the village of Cerna had at the 2002 Romanian census a population of 2,427, and together with three smaller villages the population of the entire commune was 4,227. Estimates of the number of Megleno-Romanians in this village vary from 1,200 to 2,000. \n\nIn 1940, according to the stipulations of the [[Treaty of Craiova]], the Bulgarian population from Cerna was resettled to [[Southern Dobruja]], mainly to the village of Turcsmil, which was renamed [[Nova Cherna]] (New Cerna) in the memory of their former place of origin.\n\n==Notable natives==\n* [[Panait Cerna]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1155121}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cerna, Tulcea}}\n\n{{Tulcea County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Tulcea County]]\n\n{{Tulcea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerna,_Tulcea"}
{"title_page": "Ronald S. Weinstein", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Ronald S. Weinstein, M.D.\n| image = 201105033 Ronald Weinstein 5x7 DSC5436.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1938|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Schenectady, New York]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona College of Medicine]]<br>[[Rush Medical College]]\n| alma_mater = [[Union College]] (BS)<br>[[Tufts Medical School]] (MD)\n| known_for = Telepathology, Urinary Bladder Cancer, Science Education\n| influences =   [[Albert Szent-Gyorgyi]], MD, PhD Stanley Bullivant, PhD  William C. Moloney, MD [[Benjamin Castleman]], MD  John H. Knowles, MD\n| field = Cancer biology, Multi-drug resistance\n}}\n'''Ronald S. Weinstein, M.D.''' (born November 20, 1938) is an American [[Pathology|pathologist]]. He is a professor at the [[University of Arizona College of Medicine|University of Arizona College of Medicine-Tucson]]. Weinstein served for 32 years as an academic pathology department chair, in Chicago, Illinois and then Tucson, Arizona, while also serving as a serial entrepreneur engaged in university [[technology transfer]].\n\nHe is past president of six medical organizations, including the [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]] and the International Society for Urological Pathology, which he co-founded. He is a cancer researcher, an educator, and an inventor.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWeinstein was born on November 20, 1938, in [[Schenectady, New York]].<ref name=\"Visionary\">{{cite news|last1=Erikson|first1=Jane|title=Biomedical visionary|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/222470548/?terms=ronald%2Bweinstein|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=July 10, 2005}}</ref> He completed his undergraduate studies at [[Union College]] in Schenectady. In college, he was a Ford Foundation-funded Congressional Intern in Washington, D.C., in the office of US Representative [[Samuel S. Stratton]], and studied governmental affairs.  His primary focus remained medical science research.  After graduation from Union College, Weinstein spent three summers working as a [[chemist]] at [[Marine Biological Laboratory|Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory]]. Weinstein obtained his M.D. degree from [[Tufts Medical School]] in Boston in 1965. In [[medical school]], he had been a [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH) post-sophomore [[research fellow]] and had done research on high-resolution [[freeze-fracture]] [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] with Stanley Bullivant, PhD, a biophysicist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] faculty member.  As an MGH pathology resident, he co-authored research papers on [[intercellular junctions]], [[cancer cell]], and red [[cell membrane]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McNutt|first=N. Scott|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|date=1970-12-01|title=THE ULTRASTRUCTURE OF THE NEXUS: A Correlated Thin-Section and Freeze-Cleave Study|journal=The Journal of Cell Biology|language=en|volume=47|issue=3|pages=666\u2013688|doi=10.1083/jcb.47.3.666|issn=0021-9525|pmid=5531667|pmc=2108148}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=McNutt|first=N. Scott|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|date=1969-08-08|title=Carcinoma of the Cervix: Deficiency of Nexus Intercellular Junctions|journal=Science|language=en|volume=165|issue=3893|pages=597\u2013598|doi=10.1126/science.165.3893.597|issn=0036-8075|pmid=5815840|bibcode=1969Sci...165..597M}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|date=1969-07-10|title=The Structure of Cell Membranes|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=281|issue=2|pages=86\u201389|doi=10.1056/nejm196907102810206|issn=0028-4793|pmid=4891366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steck|first=Theodore L.|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|last3=Straus|first3=John H.|last4=Wallach|first4=Donald F. H.|date=1970-04-10|title=Inside-Out Red Cell Membrane Vesicles: Preparation and Puirification|journal=Science|language=en|volume=168|issue=3928|pages=255\u2013257|doi=10.1126/science.168.3928.255|issn=0036-8075|pmid=5418644|bibcode=1970Sci...168..255S}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the Vietnam War, he served as a [[United States Air Force]] [[Major]] at the Aerospace Medical Research Laboratory, [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base]], in Dayton, Ohio, where he was involved in [[toxicology]] research, and participated in computer science courses in computer programming and system design at the [[Air Force Institute of Technology]] on the same campus. He researched the potential sources of toxic chronic chemical injury, from trace amounts of rocket propellants and oxidizers, to [[Airman|airmen]] working in [[Titan missile]] silo environments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WEINSTEIN|first=R|title=Effects of continuous inhalation of dichloromethane in the mouse: Morphologic and functional observations*1|journal=Toxicology and Applied Pharmacology|volume=23|issue=4|pages=660\u2013679|doi=10.1016/0041-008x(72)90107-x|pmid=4118878|year=1972}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=George|first2=Marilyn E.|last3=Steingart|first3=Richard H.|title=Contribution of Heinz bodies to alterations in red cell deformability|journal=Toxicology and Applied Pharmacology|volume=32|issue=3|pages=545\u2013558|doi=10.1016/0041-008x(75)90119-2|pmid=1154414|year=1975}}</ref>  From 1972 to 1975, he was Professor of Pathology at Tufts University School of Medicine.  He continued his research on normal cell membranes and cancer cell membranes and initiated research on animal models for urinary bladder cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scott McNutt|first=N.|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|title=Membrane ultrastructure at mammalian intercellular junctions|journal=Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology|volume=26|pages=45\u2013101|doi=10.1016/0079-6107(73)90017-5|pmid=4122630|year=1973}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|date=1976-07-01|title=Changes in Plasma Membrane Structure Associated with Malignant Transformation in Human Urinary Bladder Epithelium|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/36/7_Part_2/2518|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=36|issue=7 Part 2|pages=2518\u20132524|issn=0008-5472|pmid=1277160}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Structure and Function of Intercellular Junctions in Cancer|volume = 23|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Merk|first2=Frederick B.|last3=Alroy|first3=Joseph|pages=23\u201389|doi=10.1016/s0065-230x(08)60543-6|pmid = 179291|series = Advances in Cancer Research|year = 1976|isbn = 9780120066230}}</ref>  In 1975, Weinstein was named the Harriet Blair Borland Professor and chairman of pathology at [[Rush Medical College]] in Chicago. Weinstein participated in National Cancer Institute (NCI) funded cancer clinical trials as director of the National Bladder Cancer Group's Central Pathology Laboratory (1982\u20131990),  which qualified patients for inclusion in urinary [[bladder cancer]] clinical trials.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heney|first=NM|last2=Koontz|first2=WW|last3=Barton|first3=B|last4=Soloway|first4=M|last5=Trump|first5=DL|last6=Hazra|first6=T|last7=Weinstein|first7=RS|date=December 1988|title=Intravesical thiotepa versus mitomycin C in patients with Ta, T1 and TIS transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder: a phase III prospective randomized study.|journal=The Journal of Urology|language=en|volume=140|issue=6|pages=1390\u20131393|doi=10.1016/S0022-5347(17)42052-0|pmid=3143016|issn=0022-5347}}</ref> In addition, he was Founding Director of the NCI-funded National Urinary Bladder Flow Cytometry Network which established clinical [[flow cytometry]] laboratory procedures and standards (1985\u20131990).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aamodt|first=R. L.|last2=Coon|first2=J. S.|last3=Deitch|first3=A.|last4=White|first4=R. W. deVere|last5=Koss|first5=L. G.|last6=Melamed|first6=M. R.|last7=Weinstein|first7=R. S.|last8=Wheeless|first8=L. L.|date=1992-02-01|title=Flow cytometric evaluation of bladder cancer: recommendations of the NCI flow cytometry network for bladder cancer|journal=World Journal of Urology|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=63\u201367|doi=10.1007/BF00186094|issn=0724-4983}}</ref> In 1990, Weinstein was named [[Professor]] and [[Chair]] of Pathology at The University of Arizona's College of Medicine. He studied cancer multi-drug resistance at the Arizona Cancer Center.<ref name=\"Weinstein 2720\u20132726\">{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Jakate|first2=Shriram M.|last3=Dominguez|first3=Jose M.|last4=Lebovitz|first4=Miriam D.|last5=Koukoulis|first5=George K.|last6=Kuszak|first6=Jerome R.|last7=Klusens|first7=Larry F.|last8=Grogan|first8=Thomas M.|last9=Saclarides|first9=Theodore J.|date=1991-05-15|title=Relationship of the Expression of the Multidrug Resistance Gene Product (P-Glycoprotein) in Human Colon Carcinoma to Local Tumor Aggressiveness and Lymph Node Metastasis|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/51/10/2720|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=51|issue=10|pages=2720\u20132726|issn=0008-5472|pmid=1673639}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grogan|first=T. M.|last2=Spier|first2=C. M.|last3=Salmon|first3=S. E.|last4=Matzner|first4=M.|last5=Rybski|first5=J.|last6=Weinstein|first6=R. S.|last7=Scheper|first7=R. J.|last8=Dalton|first8=W. S.|date=1993-01-15|title=P-glycoprotein expression in human plasma cell myeloma: correlation with prior chemotherapy|journal=Blood|language=en|volume=81|issue=2|pages=490\u2013495|issn=0006-4971|pmid=8093668|doi=10.1182/blood.V81.2.490.490}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bellamy|first=W. T.|last2=Mendibles|first2=Pamela|last3=Bontje|first3=Petra|last4=Thompson|first4=Floyd|last5=Richter|first5=Lynne|last6=Weinstein|first6=Ronald S.|last7=Grogan|first7=Thomas M.|last8=Gorgan|first8=T. M.|date=1996-01-01|title=Development of an orthotopic SCID mouse-human tumor xenograft model displaying the multidrug-resistant phenotype|journal=Cancer Chemotherapy and Pharmacology|language=en|volume=37|issue=4|pages=305\u2013316|doi=10.1007/s002800050390|pmid=8548875|issn=0344-5704}}</ref> He also holds academic appointments in the university's [[University of Arizona College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]] and its Mel and Enid Zuckerman College of Public Health.\n\nIn 1988\u201389, Weinstein was president of the [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]].<ref>[https://www.uscap.org/about/history/past-presidents/ronald-s-weinstein Past Presidents: Ronald S. Weinstein]. [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]]. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref>  In 1995\u20131996, he was president of the International Society for Urological Pathology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isupweb.org/isup/about-isup/history/|title=History {{!}} ISUP|website=isupweb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> In 2003\u201304, he was president of the [[American Telemedicine Association]].<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.americantelemed.org/about/past-presidents Past Presidents]. [[American Telemedicine Association]]. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref> In 2010\u20132011, he was president of the Association for Pathology Informatics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pathologyinformatics.org/api_governing_council.php|title=API Governing Council - Association for Pathology Informatics|website=www.pathologyinformatics.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Development of telepathology and telemedicine==\nWhile a department chair at Rush Medical College in Chicago, Weinstein carried out the first public demonstration of satellite-enabled robotic [[telepathology]], between El Paso, TX. and Washington, DC, in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/wellness/1986/08/27/the-next-best-thing-to-being/a75848be-4790-447e-b0eb-dafa0b8714e9/|title=The Next Best Thing To Being|last=Colburn|first=Don|date=1986-08-27|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In 1993, Weinstein patented telepathology systems and telepathology diagnostic networks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cucoranu|first=IoanC.|last2=Pantanowitz|first2=Liron|last3=Parwani|first3=AnilV.|last4=Vepa|first4=Suryanarayana|last5=Weinstein|first5=RonaldS.|date=2014-01-01|title=Digital pathology: A systematic evaluation of the patent landscape|journal=Journal of Pathology Informatics|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16|doi=10.4103/2153-3539.133112|pmid=25057430|pmc=4060404}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EY7wCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA581&dq=9781482236590#v=onepage&q=9781482236590&f=false|title=Telemedicine and Electronic Medicine|last=Eren|first=Halit|last2=Webster|first2=John G.|date=2015-12-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781482236590|location=|pages=581\u2013596|language=en}}</ref> He established an international telepathology service network linking the United States, Mexico and China.<ref name=\"Weinstein 1995\">{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=RS|last2=Bhattacharyya|first2=A|last3=Yu|first3=YP|last4=Davis|first4=JR|last5=Byers|first5=JM|last6=Graham|first6=AR|last7=Martinez|first7=R|date=1995|title=Pathology consultation services via the Arizona-International Telemedicine Network.|journal=Archives d'Anatomie et de Cytologie Pathologiques|language=en|volume=43|issue=4|pages=219\u201326|issn=0395-501X|pmid=8526556}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halliday|first=Bradford E|last2=Bhattacharyya|first2=A.K|last3=Graham|first3=Anna R|last4=Davis|first4=John R|last5=Leavitt|first5=S.Anne|last6=Nagle|first6=Ray B|last7=Mclaughlin|first7=Wendy J|last8=Rivas|first8=Ricardo A|last9=Martinez|first9=Ralph|title=Diagnostic accuracy of an international static-imaging telepathology consultation service|journal=Human Pathology|volume=28|issue=1|pages=17\u201321|doi=10.1016/s0046-8177(97)90273-2|pmid=9013826|year=1997}}</ref>  Weinstein has been referred to as the \u201cfather of telepathology\u201d in a 2011 journal article written by a student and a faculty member from an Indian medical school.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sankaye | first1 = Smita | last2 = Kachewar | first2 = Sushil | year = 2011 | title = Telepathology for effective healthcare in developing nations | journal = The Australasian Medical Journal | volume = 4 | issue = 11| pages = 592\u2013595 | pmc = 3562914 | pmid = 23386872 | doi = 10.4066/AMJ.2011.855 }}</ref> Weinstein received the Association of Pathology Informatics\u2019 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>[https://www.pathologyinformatics.org/api_lifetime_achievement_award.php API Lifetime Achievement Award]. Association of Pathology Informatics. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he became Founding Director of the Arizona Telemedicine Program (ATP), which he co-founded with Arizona State Representative Robert \"Bob\" Burns.<ref name=\"AJP\">{{cite web|last1=Del Grande|first1=David J.|title=UA telehealth pioneer sees program thriving|url=https://azjewishpost.com/2017/ua-telehealth-pioneer-sees-program-thriving/|website=[[Arizona Jewish Post]]|accessdate=November 18, 2017|date=September 22, 2017}}</ref> The ATP links 160 sites in 70 communities by broadband telecommunications and has provided telemedicine services for 1.4 million cases in 61 subspecialties of medicine. He became executive director of the Institute for Advanced Telemedicine and Telehealth (T-Health Institute), a Phoenix division of the ATP, in 2004.\n\nThe ATP includes: the Tucson-based Warren Street Clinic, a dual-purpose clinical education facility which provides real-time tele-medicine specialty services across the network and hands-on training for participants in the ATP's regularly scheduled full day telemedicine courses;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://telemedicine.arizona.edu/training|title=Training {{!}} telemedicine.arizona.edu|website=telemedicine.arizona.edu|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> the T-Health Amphitheater, a video conferencing center located at the T-Health Institute on the Phoenix Biomedical Campus is in downtown Phoenix;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://telemedicine.arizona.edu/thealth|title=T-Health Institute {{!}} telemedicine.arizona.edu|website=telemedicine.arizona.edu|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>  and the federally-funded Southwest Telehealth Resource Center, which provides technical support and staff training for telehealth programs in the southwestern United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ruralhealthinfo.org/rural-monitor/sw-telehealth-resource-center/|title=Southwest Telehealth Resource Center Helps Rural Providers Connect - The Rural Monitor|date=2017-08-23|work=The Rural Monitor|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Research and development==\n'''Technology innovations, classifications, and validations'''\n\nWeinstein has had a career-long interest in the development of medical science research technologies including: freeze-fracture electron microscopy;<ref>Weinstein RS, McNutt NS: Heat etching with a Bullivant Type II simple freeze cleave device. Proc Electron Micros Soc Am 1970; 28:106 107</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Branton|first=Daniel|last2=Bullivant|first2=Stanley|last3=Gilula|first3=Norton B.|last4=Karnovsky|first4=Morris J.|last5=Moor|first5=H.|last6=M\u00fchlethaler|first6=K.|last7=Northcote|first7=D. H.|last8=Packer|first8=Lester|last9=Satir|first9=Birgit|date=1975|title=Freeze-Etching Nomenclature|jstor=1740879|journal=Science|volume=190|issue=4209|pages=54\u201356|doi=10.1126/science.1166299|pmid=1166299|bibcode=1975Sci...190...54B}}</ref> urinary bladder flow cytometry;<ref>Coon JS, Weinstein RS, (ed): Diagnostic Flow Cytometry.  Williams and Wilkens, Co., Baltimore, pp. 1-199, 1991</ref> image analysis;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bacus|first=JW|last2=Wiley|first2=EL|last3=Galbraith|first3=W|last4=Marshall|first4=PN|last5=Wilbanks|first5=GD|last6=Weinstein|first6=RS|date=June 1984|title=Malignant cell detection and cervical cancer screening.|journal=Analytical and Quantitative Cytology|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|pages=121\u201330|issn=0190-0471|pmid=6465697}}</ref> holographic microscopy;<ref>{{Cite book|title=X-Ray Microscopy II|last=Haddad|first=W. S.|last2=Cullen|first2=D.|last3=Boyer|first3=K.|last4=Rhodes|first4=C. K.|last5=Solem|first5=J. C.|last6=Weinstein|first6=R. S.|date=1988|publisher=Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg|isbn=9783662144909|series=Springer Series in Optical Sciences|pages=284\u2013287|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-39246-0_49}}</ref> robotic telepathology;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=RS|last2=Bloom|first2=KJ|last3=Rozek|first3=LS|date=July 1987|title=Telepathology and the networking of pathology diagnostic services.|journal=Archives of Pathology & Laboratory Medicine|language=en|volume=111|issue=7|pages=646\u201352|issn=0003-9985|pmid=3606341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EY7wCgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1&dq=Weinstein+RS,+%E2%80%9CTelepathology+system+development+and+implementation%E2%80%9D#v=onepage&q=Weinstein%20RS,%20%E2%80%9CTelepathology%20system%20development%20and%20implementation%E2%80%9D&f=false|title=Telemedicine and Electronic Medicine|last=Eren|first=Halit|last2=Webster|first2=John G.|date=2015-12-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781482236590|location=|pages=577\u2013591|language=en}}</ref> quantitative immunohistochemistry;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beck|first=William T.|last2=Grogan|first2=Thomas M.|last3=Willman|first3=Cheryl L.|last4=Cordon-Cardo|first4=Carlos|last5=Parham|first5=David M.|last6=Kuttesch|first6=John F.|last7=Andreeff|first7=Michael|last8=Bates|first8=Susan E.|last9=Berard|first9=Costan W.|date=1996-07-01|title=Methods to Detect P-Glycoprotein-associated Multidrug Resistance in Patients' Tumors: Consensus Recommendations|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/56/13/3010|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=56|issue=13|pages=3010\u20133020|issn=0008-5472|pmid=8674056}}</ref> array light microscopy;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Descour|first2=Michael R.|last3=Liang|first3=Chen|last4=Barker|first4=Gail|last5=Scott|first5=Katherine M.|last6=Richter|first6=Lynne|last7=Krupinski|first7=Elizabeth A.|last8=Bhattacharyya|first8=Achyut K.|last9=Davis|first9=John R.|title=An array microscope for ultrarapid virtual slide processing and telepathology. Design, fabrication, and validation study|journal=Human Pathology|volume=35|issue=11|pages=1303\u20131314|doi=10.1016/j.humpath.2004.09.002|pmid=15668886|year=2004}}</ref> and digital pathology.<ref>Kayser K, Molnar B, Weinstein RS. Digital Pathology Virtual Slide Technology in Tissue-based Diagnosis, Research and Education. VSV Interdisciplinary Medical Publishing, Berlin'','' 2006, pp.1-193</ref>\n\n'''Cancer research'''\n\nWeinstein studied mechanisms of carcinogenesis, pre-cancer development, and cancer invasion and metastasis.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Weinstein 2720\u20132726\"/>  He studied cell membrane properties in normal epithelium, pre-cancers and cancers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pigVIclI3hQC&pg=PA240&dq=Weinstein+RS,+Pauli+BU:++Cell+junctions+and+the+biological+behavior+of+cancer.++In:+Stoker+M,+Bock+G,+Clark+S,+eds.,+Junctional+Complexes+in+Epithelial+Cells.++(Ciba+Foundation+Symposium+125.)++John+Wiley+#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Junctional Complexes of Epithelial Cells|last=Bock|first=Gregory R.|last2=Clark|first2=Sarah|date=2008-04-30|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470513415|location=|pages=240\u2013260|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Medical science education reform'''\n\nTo encourage the democratization of medical science knowledge, Weinstein developed a series of class-room courses on \u201cmechanisms of diseases\u201d that have been utilized in middle schools, high schools, and universities.<ref>Weinstein RS, Waer AL, Weinstein JB, Briehl MM, Krupinski EA. Second Flexner Century. The democratization of medical knowledge:  repurposing a general pathology course into multigrade-level \u201cgateway\u201d courses. Academic Pathology 2017; 4: 1-12. doi: 10.1177/2374289517718872</ref>\n\n'''Global health'''\n\nWeinstein was involved in the creation and evaluation of multi-national telemedicine and telepathology programs.<ref name=\"Weinstein 1995\"/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Vega|first=Silvio|last2=Marciscano|first2=Ivette|last3=Holcomb|first3=Michael|last4=Erps|first4=Kristine A.|last5=Major|first5=Janet|last6=Lopez|first6=Ana Maria|last7=Barker|first7=Gail P.|last8=Weinstein|first8=Ronald S.|date=2013-08-09|title=Testing a Top-Down Strategy for Establishing a Sustainable Telemedicine Program in a Developing Country: The Arizona Telemedicine Program\u2013U.S. Army\u2013Republic of Panama Initiative|journal=Telemedicine and E-Health|volume=19|issue=10|pages=746\u2013753|doi=10.1089/tmj.2013.0025|pmid=23931731|issn=1530-5627}}</ref> In 1981\u20131983, he was International Councilor of the International Academy of Pathology.  In 1998\u20131999, he was president of the International Council of Societies of Pathology, a World Health Organization registered entity.  Weinstein was an advisor on telemedicine for the Minister of Health in Mexico, China, and Panama.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was a frequent lecturer at international medical conferences.\n\n'''Publications'''\n\nWeinstein has published over 300 articles in peer reviewed scientific and pathology journals, 57 book chapters, and 11 books.  These have been cited over 11,000 times in the science literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ronald_Weinstein2|title=Ronald S Weinstein {{!}} The University of Arizona (UA) {{!}} ResearchGate|website=ResearchGate|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\nWeinstein is president emeritus of the American Telemedicine Association.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013, he was inducted into the United States Distance Learning Association \"Hall-of-Fame\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usdla.org/awards/hall-of-fame/|title=Hall of Fame|website=www.usdla.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>  The T-Health Amphitheater, in Phoenix, AZ, a \"Classroom-of-the-Future\" co-designed by Weinstein, received the 21st Century Achievement Award, Education and Academia category, from the International Computer World Honors program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cwhonors.org/archives/2008/index.htm|title=Computerworld Honors Program - 2008 Awards Ceremony|website=cwhonors.org|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Involvement in business==\nIn 1982, Weinstein, and his sister and business partner, Beth Newburger, co-founded OWLCAT, Inc., an early entrant in the IBM computer-based, [[S.A.T.]] examination preparation course business.  Two years later, OWLCAT, Inc. was acquired by [[Digital Research Inc.|Digital Research, Inc.]] (DRI).  DRI successfully marketed the OWLCAT education software products.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Pq3POofPsBEC&pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=OWLCAT+Digital+Research+Inc#v=onepage&q=OWLCAT%20Digital%20Research%20Inc&f=false|title=PC Mag|last=Inc|first=Ziff Davis|date=1984-09-18|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|isbn=|location=|pages=321|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Weinstein and Newburger co-founded Corabi International Telemetrics, Inc.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-04-19/business/8701300232_1_chicago-technology-park-research-center-west-side/2|title=Dry Spell Is Ending For High-tech Oasis|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2018-01-17|language=en}}</ref>  Corabi equipped several [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|US Department of Veterans Affairs]] Medical Centers with robotic telepathology systems.  These were used for [[Proof of concept|proof-of-concept]] studies validating telepathology for clinical use.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dunn|first=Bruce E|last2=Almagro|first2=Urias A|last3=Choi|first3=Hongyung|last4=Sheth|first4=Neela K|last5=Arnold|first5=James S|last6=Recla|first6=Daniel L|last7=Krupinski|first7=Elizabeth A|last8=Graham|first8=Anna R|last9=Weinstein|first9=Ronald S|title=Dynamic-robotic telepathology: Department of veterans affairs feasibility study|journal=Human Pathology|volume=28|issue=1|pages=8\u201312|doi=10.1016/s0046-8177(97)90271-9|pmid=9013824|year=1997}}</ref> In 2001, Weinstein co-founded DMetrix, Inc., a [[University spin-off|spin-out]] company of The University of Arizona's [[University of Arizona College of Optical Sciences|College of Optical Sciences]].  DMetrix, Inc. was awarded 29 US Patents on its DX-40 ultra-rapid array microscope digital slide scanner.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cucoranu|first=IoanC.|last2=Pantanowitz|first2=Liron|last3=Parwani|first3=AnilV.|last4=Vepa|first4=Suryanarayana|last5=Weinstein|first5=RonaldS.|date=2014-01-01|title=Digital pathology: A systematic evaluation of the patent landscape|journal=Journal of Pathology Informatics|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16|doi=10.4103/2153-3539.133112|pmid=25057430|pmc=4060404}}</ref>\n\nFor his work in university technology transfer, he received the University of Arizona's \"2012 Technology Innovator-of-the-Year\" Award.<ref name=\"Beal\">{{cite web|last1=Beal|first1=Tom|title=UA honors innovators for ideas to save lives|url=http://tucson.com/business/local/ua-honors-innovators-for-ideas-to-save-lives/article_c3047d4a-d392-54d9-84f2-09a91e13a949.html|website=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=March 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1964, Weinstein married the former Mary Corabi; they met while they were both working at Woods Hole. They have two grown children and two grandsons.<ref name=\"Visionary\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alphaomegaalpha.org/leaders.html Weinstein's 1982 interview of Benjamin Castleman] archived in the [[United States National Library of Medicine|National Library of Medicine]]'s \u201c[[Alpha Omega Alpha|AOA Leaders in Medicine]]\u201d video series\n* [https://swtrc.wistia.com/medias/9pmhcqdg3l Weinstein's lecture at the \u201cFred and Janet Sanfilippo Distinguished Leadership\u201d event.] at [[Johns Hopkins Medical School]] describing his work on improving [[health literacy]] for K-12 students\n* [https://isupweb.org/isup/ International Society for Urological Pathology]\n* [http://www.telemedicine.arizona.edu/ Arizona Telemedicine Program]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Ronald}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:Rush Medical College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:Union College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Ronald S. Weinstein, M.D.\n| image = 201105033 Ronald Weinstein 5x7 DSC5436.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1938|11|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Schenectady, New York]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Arizona College of Medicine]]<br>[[Rush Medical College]]\n| alma_mater = [[Union College]] (BS)<br>[[Tufts Medical School]] (MD)\n| known_for = Telepathology, Urinary Bladder Cancer, Science Education\n| influences =   [[Albert Szent-Gyorgyi]], MD, PhD Stanley Bullivant, PhD  William C. Moloney, MD [[Benjamin Castleman]], MD  John H. Knowles, MD\n| field = Cancer biology, Multi-drug resistance\n}}\n'''Ronald S. Weinstein, M.D.''' (born November 20, 1938) is an American [[Pathology|pathologist]]. He is a professor at the [[University of Arizona College of Medicine|University of Arizona College of Medicine-Tucson]]. Weinstein served for 32 years as an academic pathology department chair, in Chicago, Illinois and then Tucson, Arizona, while also serving as a serial entrepreneur engaged in university [[technology transfer]].\n\nHe is past president of six medical organizations, including the [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]] and the International Society for Urological Pathology, which he co-founded. He is a cancer researcher, an educator, and an inventor.\n\n==Early life and education==\nWeinstein was born on November 20, 1938, in [[Schenectady, New York]].<ref name=\"Visionary\">{{cite news|last1=Erikson|first1=Jane|title=Biomedical visionary|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/222470548/?terms=ronald%2Bweinstein|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=July 10, 2005}}</ref> He completed his undergraduate studies at [[Union College]] in Schenectady. In college, he was a Ford Foundation-funded Congressional Intern in Washington, D.C., in the office of US Representative [[Samuel S. Stratton]], and studied governmental affairs.  His primary focus remained medical science research.  After graduation from Union College, Weinstein spent three summers working as a [[chemist]] at [[Marine Biological Laboratory|Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory]]. Weinstein obtained his M.D. degree from [[Tufts Medical School]] in Boston in 1965. In [[medical school]], he had been a [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH) post-sophomore [[research fellow]] and had done research on high-resolution [[freeze-fracture]] [[Electron microscope|electron microscopy]] with Stanley Bullivant, PhD, a biophysicist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] faculty member.  As an MGH pathology resident, he co-authored research papers on [[intercellular junctions]], [[cancer cell]], and red [[cell membrane]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McNutt|first=N. Scott|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|date=1970-12-01|title=THE ULTRASTRUCTURE OF THE NEXUS: A Correlated Thin-Section and Freeze-Cleave Study|journal=The Journal of Cell Biology|language=en|volume=47|issue=3|pages=666\u2013688|doi=10.1083/jcb.47.3.666|issn=0021-9525|pmid=5531667|pmc=2108148}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=McNutt|first=N. Scott|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|date=1969-08-08|title=Carcinoma of the Cervix: Deficiency of Nexus Intercellular Junctions|journal=Science|language=en|volume=165|issue=3893|pages=597\u2013598|doi=10.1126/science.165.3893.597|issn=0036-8075|pmid=5815840|bibcode=1969Sci...165..597M}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|date=1969-07-10|title=The Structure of Cell Membranes|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=281|issue=2|pages=86\u201389|doi=10.1056/nejm196907102810206|issn=0028-4793|pmid=4891366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steck|first=Theodore L.|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|last3=Straus|first3=John H.|last4=Wallach|first4=Donald F. H.|date=1970-04-10|title=Inside-Out Red Cell Membrane Vesicles: Preparation and Puirification|journal=Science|language=en|volume=168|issue=3928|pages=255\u2013257|doi=10.1126/science.168.3928.255|issn=0036-8075|pmid=5418644|bibcode=1970Sci...168..255S}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDuring the Vietnam War, he served as a [[United States Air Force]] [[Major]] at the Aerospace Medical Research Laboratory, [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base]], in Dayton, Ohio, where he was involved in [[toxicology]] research, and participated in computer science courses in computer programming and system design at the [[Air Force Institute of Technology]] on the same campus. He researched the potential sources of toxic chronic chemical injury, from trace amounts of rocket propellants and oxidizers, to [[Airman|airmen]] working in [[Titan missile]] silo environments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=WEINSTEIN|first=R|title=Effects of continuous inhalation of dichloromethane in the mouse: Morphologic and functional observations*1|journal=Toxicology and Applied Pharmacology|volume=23|issue=4|pages=660\u2013679|doi=10.1016/0041-008x(72)90107-x|pmid=4118878|year=1972}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=George|first2=Marilyn E.|last3=Steingart|first3=Richard H.|title=Contribution of Heinz bodies to alterations in red cell deformability|journal=Toxicology and Applied Pharmacology|volume=32|issue=3|pages=545\u2013558|doi=10.1016/0041-008x(75)90119-2|pmid=1154414|year=1975}}</ref>  From 1972 to 1975, he was Professor of Pathology at Tufts University School of Medicine.  He continued his research on normal cell membranes and cancer cell membranes and initiated research on animal models for urinary bladder cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scott McNutt|first=N.|last2=Weinstein|first2=Ronald S.|title=Membrane ultrastructure at mammalian intercellular junctions|journal=Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology|volume=26|pages=45\u2013101|doi=10.1016/0079-6107(73)90017-5|pmid=4122630|year=1973}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|date=1976-07-01|title=Changes in Plasma Membrane Structure Associated with Malignant Transformation in Human Urinary Bladder Epithelium|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/36/7_Part_2/2518|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=36|issue=7 Part 2|pages=2518\u20132524|issn=0008-5472|pmid=1277160}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The Structure and Function of Intercellular Junctions in Cancer|volume = 23|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Merk|first2=Frederick B.|last3=Alroy|first3=Joseph|pages=23\u201389|doi=10.1016/s0065-230x(08)60543-6|pmid = 179291|series = Advances in Cancer Research|year = 1976|isbn = 9780120066230}}</ref>  In 1975, Weinstein was named the Harriet Blair Borland Professor and chairman of pathology at [[Rush Medical College]] in Chicago. Weinstein participated in National Cancer Institute (NCI) funded cancer clinical trials as director of the National Bladder Cancer Group's Central Pathology Laboratory (1982\u20131990),  which qualified patients for inclusion in urinary [[bladder cancer]] clinical trials.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heney|first=NM|last2=Koontz|first2=WW|last3=Barton|first3=B|last4=Soloway|first4=M|last5=Trump|first5=DL|last6=Hazra|first6=T|last7=Weinstein|first7=RS|date=December 1988|title=Intravesical thiotepa versus mitomycin C in patients with Ta, T1 and TIS transitional cell carcinoma of the bladder: a phase III prospective randomized study.|journal=The Journal of Urology|language=en|volume=140|issue=6|pages=1390\u20131393|doi=10.1016/S0022-5347(17)42052-0|pmid=3143016|issn=0022-5347}}</ref> In addition, he was Founding Director of the NCI-funded National Urinary Bladder Flow Cytometry Network which established clinical [[flow cytometry]] laboratory procedures and standards (1985\u20131990).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aamodt|first=R. L.|last2=Coon|first2=J. S.|last3=Deitch|first3=A.|last4=White|first4=R. W. deVere|last5=Koss|first5=L. G.|last6=Melamed|first6=M. R.|last7=Weinstein|first7=R. S.|last8=Wheeless|first8=L. L.|date=1992-02-01|title=Flow cytometric evaluation of bladder cancer: recommendations of the NCI flow cytometry network for bladder cancer|journal=World Journal of Urology|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=63\u201367|doi=10.1007/BF00186094|issn=0724-4983}}</ref> In 1990, Weinstein was named [[Professor]] and [[Chair]] of Pathology at The University of Arizona's College of Medicine. He studied cancer multi-drug resistance at the Arizona Cancer Center.<ref name=\"Weinstein 2720\u20132726\">{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Jakate|first2=Shriram M.|last3=Dominguez|first3=Jose M.|last4=Lebovitz|first4=Miriam D.|last5=Koukoulis|first5=George K.|last6=Kuszak|first6=Jerome R.|last7=Klusens|first7=Larry F.|last8=Grogan|first8=Thomas M.|last9=Saclarides|first9=Theodore J.|date=1991-05-15|title=Relationship of the Expression of the Multidrug Resistance Gene Product (P-Glycoprotein) in Human Colon Carcinoma to Local Tumor Aggressiveness and Lymph Node Metastasis|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/51/10/2720|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=51|issue=10|pages=2720\u20132726|issn=0008-5472|pmid=1673639}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grogan|first=T. M.|last2=Spier|first2=C. M.|last3=Salmon|first3=S. E.|last4=Matzner|first4=M.|last5=Rybski|first5=J.|last6=Weinstein|first6=R. S.|last7=Scheper|first7=R. J.|last8=Dalton|first8=W. S.|date=1993-01-15|title=P-glycoprotein expression in human plasma cell myeloma: correlation with prior chemotherapy|journal=Blood|language=en|volume=81|issue=2|pages=490\u2013495|issn=0006-4971|pmid=8093668|doi=10.1182/blood.V81.2.490.490}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bellamy|first=W. T.|last2=Mendibles|first2=Pamela|last3=Bontje|first3=Petra|last4=Thompson|first4=Floyd|last5=Richter|first5=Lynne|last6=Weinstein|first6=Ronald S.|last7=Grogan|first7=Thomas M.|last8=Gorgan|first8=T. M.|date=1996-01-01|title=Development of an orthotopic SCID mouse-human tumor xenograft model displaying the multidrug-resistant phenotype|journal=Cancer Chemotherapy and Pharmacology|language=en|volume=37|issue=4|pages=305\u2013316|doi=10.1007/s002800050390|pmid=8548875|issn=0344-5704}}</ref> He also holds academic appointments in the university's [[University of Arizona College of Pharmacy|College of Pharmacy]] and its Mel and Enid Zuckerman College of Public Health.\n\nIn 1988\u201389, Weinstein was president of the [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]].<ref>[https://www.uscap.org/about/history/past-presidents/ronald-s-weinstein Past Presidents: Ronald S. Weinstein]. [[United States and Canadian Academy of Pathology]]. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref>  In 1995\u20131996, he was president of the International Society for Urological Pathology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isupweb.org/isup/about-isup/history/|title=History {{!}} ISUP|website=isupweb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> In 2003\u201304, he was president of the [[American Telemedicine Association]].<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.americantelemed.org/about/past-presidents Past Presidents]. [[American Telemedicine Association]]. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref> In 2010\u20132011, he was president of the Association for Pathology Informatics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pathologyinformatics.org/api_governing_council.php|title=API Governing Council - Association for Pathology Informatics|website=www.pathologyinformatics.org|language=en|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Development of telepathology and telemedicine==\nWhile a department chair at Rush Medical College in Chicago, Weinstein carried out the first public demonstration of satellite-enabled robotic [[telepathology]], between El Paso, TX. and Washington, DC, in 1986.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/wellness/1986/08/27/the-next-best-thing-to-being/a75848be-4790-447e-b0eb-dafa0b8714e9/|title=The Next Best Thing To Being|last=Colburn|first=Don|date=1986-08-27|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In 1993, Weinstein patented telepathology systems and telepathology diagnostic networks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cucoranu|first=IoanC.|last2=Pantanowitz|first2=Liron|last3=Parwani|first3=AnilV.|last4=Vepa|first4=Suryanarayana|last5=Weinstein|first5=RonaldS.|date=2014-01-01|title=Digital pathology: A systematic evaluation of the patent landscape|journal=Journal of Pathology Informatics|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16|doi=10.4103/2153-3539.133112|pmid=25057430|pmc=4060404}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EY7wCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA581&dq=9781482236590#v=onepage&q=9781482236590&f=false|title=Telemedicine and Electronic Medicine|last=Eren|first=Halit|last2=Webster|first2=John G.|date=2015-12-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781482236590|location=|pages=581\u2013596|language=en}}</ref> He established an international telepathology service network linking the United States, Mexico and China.<ref name=\"Weinstein 1995\">{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=RS|last2=Bhattacharyya|first2=A|last3=Yu|first3=YP|last4=Davis|first4=JR|last5=Byers|first5=JM|last6=Graham|first6=AR|last7=Martinez|first7=R|date=1995|title=Pathology consultation services via the Arizona-International Telemedicine Network.|journal=Archives d'Anatomie et de Cytologie Pathologiques|language=en|volume=43|issue=4|pages=219\u201326|issn=0395-501X|pmid=8526556}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halliday|first=Bradford E|last2=Bhattacharyya|first2=A.K|last3=Graham|first3=Anna R|last4=Davis|first4=John R|last5=Leavitt|first5=S.Anne|last6=Nagle|first6=Ray B|last7=Mclaughlin|first7=Wendy J|last8=Rivas|first8=Ricardo A|last9=Martinez|first9=Ralph|title=Diagnostic accuracy of an international static-imaging telepathology consultation service|journal=Human Pathology|volume=28|issue=1|pages=17\u201321|doi=10.1016/s0046-8177(97)90273-2|pmid=9013826|year=1997}}</ref>  Weinstein has been referred to as the \u201cfather of telepathology\u201d in a 2011 journal article written by a student and a faculty member from an Indian medical school.<ref>Sankaye, Smita, and Kachewar, Sushil (2011). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3562914/ Telepathology for effective healthcare in developing nations]. ''The Australasian Medical Journal''. 4(11):592-595. Retrieved November 20, 2017.</ref> Weinstein received the Association of Pathology Informatics\u2019 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>[https://www.pathologyinformatics.org/api_lifetime_achievement_award.php API Lifetime Achievement Award]. Association of Pathology Informatics. Retrieved November 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he became Founding Director of the Arizona Telemedicine Program (ATP), which he co-founded with Arizona State Representative Robert \"Bob\" Burns.<ref name=\"AJP\">{{cite web|last1=Del Grande|first1=David J.|title=UA telehealth pioneer sees program thriving|url=https://azjewishpost.com/2017/ua-telehealth-pioneer-sees-program-thriving/|website=[[Arizona Jewish Post]]|accessdate=November 18, 2017|date=September 22, 2017}}</ref> The ATP links 160 sites in 70 communities by broadband telecommunications and has provided telemedicine services for 1.4 million cases in 61 subspecialties of medicine. He became executive director of the Institute for Advanced Telemedicine and Telehealth (T-Health Institute), a Phoenix division of the ATP, in 2004.\n\nThe ATP includes: the Tucson-based Warren Street Clinic, a dual-purpose clinical education facility which provides real-time tele-medicine specialty services across the network and hands-on training for participants in the ATP's regularly scheduled full day telemedicine courses;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://telemedicine.arizona.edu/training|title=Training {{!}} telemedicine.arizona.edu|website=telemedicine.arizona.edu|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref> the T-Health Amphitheater, a video conferencing center located at the T-Health Institute on the Phoenix Biomedical Campus is in downtown Phoenix;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://telemedicine.arizona.edu/thealth|title=T-Health Institute {{!}} telemedicine.arizona.edu|website=telemedicine.arizona.edu|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>  and the federally-funded Southwest Telehealth Resource Center, which provides technical support and staff training for telehealth programs in the southwestern United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ruralhealthinfo.org/rural-monitor/sw-telehealth-resource-center/|title=Southwest Telehealth Resource Center Helps Rural Providers Connect - The Rural Monitor|date=2017-08-23|work=The Rural Monitor|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Research and development==\n'''Technology innovations, classifications, and validations'''\n\nWeinstein has had a career-long interest in the development of medical science research technologies including: freeze-fracture electron microscopy;<ref>Weinstein RS, McNutt NS: Heat etching with a Bullivant Type II simple freeze cleave device. Proc Electron Micros Soc Am 1970; 28:106 107</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Branton|first=Daniel|last2=Bullivant|first2=Stanley|last3=Gilula|first3=Norton B.|last4=Karnovsky|first4=Morris J.|last5=Moor|first5=H.|last6=M\u00fchlethaler|first6=K.|last7=Northcote|first7=D. H.|last8=Packer|first8=Lester|last9=Satir|first9=Birgit|date=1975|title=Freeze-Etching Nomenclature|jstor=1740879|journal=Science|volume=190|issue=4209|pages=54\u201356|doi=10.1126/science.1166299|pmid=1166299|bibcode=1975Sci...190...54B}}</ref> urinary bladder flow cytometry;<ref>Coon JS, Weinstein RS, (ed): Diagnostic Flow Cytometry.  Williams and Wilkens, Co., Baltimore, pp. 1-199, 1991</ref> image analysis;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bacus|first=JW|last2=Wiley|first2=EL|last3=Galbraith|first3=W|last4=Marshall|first4=PN|last5=Wilbanks|first5=GD|last6=Weinstein|first6=RS|date=June 1984|title=Malignant cell detection and cervical cancer screening.|journal=Analytical and Quantitative Cytology|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|pages=121\u201330|issn=0190-0471|pmid=6465697}}</ref> holographic microscopy;<ref>{{Cite book|title=X-Ray Microscopy II|last=Haddad|first=W. S.|last2=Cullen|first2=D.|last3=Boyer|first3=K.|last4=Rhodes|first4=C. K.|last5=Solem|first5=J. C.|last6=Weinstein|first6=R. S.|date=1988|publisher=Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg|isbn=9783662144909|series=Springer Series in Optical Sciences|pages=284\u2013287|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-39246-0_49}}</ref> robotic telepathology;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=RS|last2=Bloom|first2=KJ|last3=Rozek|first3=LS|date=July 1987|title=Telepathology and the networking of pathology diagnostic services.|journal=Archives of Pathology & Laboratory Medicine|language=en|volume=111|issue=7|pages=646\u201352|issn=0003-9985|pmid=3606341}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=EY7wCgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1&dq=Weinstein+RS,+%E2%80%9CTelepathology+system+development+and+implementation%E2%80%9D#v=onepage&q=Weinstein%20RS,%20%E2%80%9CTelepathology%20system%20development%20and%20implementation%E2%80%9D&f=false|title=Telemedicine and Electronic Medicine|last=Eren|first=Halit|last2=Webster|first2=John G.|date=2015-12-01|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9781482236590|location=|pages=577\u2013591|language=en}}</ref> quantitative immunohistochemistry;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beck|first=William T.|last2=Grogan|first2=Thomas M.|last3=Willman|first3=Cheryl L.|last4=Cordon-Cardo|first4=Carlos|last5=Parham|first5=David M.|last6=Kuttesch|first6=John F.|last7=Andreeff|first7=Michael|last8=Bates|first8=Susan E.|last9=Berard|first9=Costan W.|date=1996-07-01|title=Methods to Detect P-Glycoprotein-associated Multidrug Resistance in Patients' Tumors: Consensus Recommendations|url=http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/56/13/3010|journal=Cancer Research|language=en|volume=56|issue=13|pages=3010\u20133020|issn=0008-5472|pmid=8674056}}</ref> array light microscopy;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinstein|first=Ronald S.|last2=Descour|first2=Michael R.|last3=Liang|first3=Chen|last4=Barker|first4=Gail|last5=Scott|first5=Katherine M.|last6=Richter|first6=Lynne|last7=Krupinski|first7=Elizabeth A.|last8=Bhattacharyya|first8=Achyut K.|last9=Davis|first9=John R.|title=An array microscope for ultrarapid virtual slide processing and telepathology. Design, fabrication, and validation study|journal=Human Pathology|volume=35|issue=11|pages=1303\u20131314|doi=10.1016/j.humpath.2004.09.002|pmid=15668886|year=2004}}</ref> and digital pathology.<ref>Kayser K, Molnar B, Weinstein RS. Digital Pathology Virtual Slide Technology in Tissue-based Diagnosis, Research and Education. VSV Interdisciplinary Medical Publishing, Berlin'','' 2006, pp.1-193</ref>\n\n'''Cancer research'''\n\nWeinstein studied mechanisms of carcinogenesis, pre-cancer development, and cancer invasion and metastasis.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Weinstein 2720\u20132726\"/>  He studied cell membrane properties in normal epithelium, pre-cancers and cancers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pigVIclI3hQC&pg=PA240&dq=Weinstein+RS,+Pauli+BU:++Cell+junctions+and+the+biological+behavior+of+cancer.++In:+Stoker+M,+Bock+G,+Clark+S,+eds.,+Junctional+Complexes+in+Epithelial+Cells.++(Ciba+Foundation+Symposium+125.)++John+Wiley+#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Junctional Complexes of Epithelial Cells|last=Bock|first=Gregory R.|last2=Clark|first2=Sarah|date=2008-04-30|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780470513415|location=|pages=240\u2013260|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Medical science education reform'''\n\nTo encourage the democratization of medical science knowledge, Weinstein developed a series of class-room courses on \u201cmechanisms of diseases\u201d that have been utilized in middle schools, high schools, and universities.<ref>Weinstein RS, Waer AL, Weinstein JB, Briehl MM, Krupinski EA. Second Flexner Century. The democratization of medical knowledge:  repurposing a general pathology course into multigrade-level \u201cgateway\u201d courses. Academic Pathology 2017; 4: 1-12. doi: 10.1177/2374289517718872</ref>\n\n'''Global health'''\n\nWeinstein was involved in the creation and evaluation of multi-national telemedicine and telepathology programs.<ref name=\"Weinstein 1995\"/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Vega|first=Silvio|last2=Marciscano|first2=Ivette|last3=Holcomb|first3=Michael|last4=Erps|first4=Kristine A.|last5=Major|first5=Janet|last6=Lopez|first6=Ana Maria|last7=Barker|first7=Gail P.|last8=Weinstein|first8=Ronald S.|date=2013-08-09|title=Testing a Top-Down Strategy for Establishing a Sustainable Telemedicine Program in a Developing Country: The Arizona Telemedicine Program\u2013U.S. Army\u2013Republic of Panama Initiative|journal=Telemedicine and E-Health|volume=19|issue=10|pages=746\u2013753|doi=10.1089/tmj.2013.0025|pmid=23931731|issn=1530-5627}}</ref> In 1981\u20131983, he was International Councilor of the International Academy of Pathology.  In 1998\u20131999, he was president of the International Council of Societies of Pathology, a World Health Organization registered entity.  Weinstein was an advisor on telemedicine for the Minister of Health in Mexico, China, and Panama.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was a frequent lecturer at international medical conferences.\n\n'''Publications'''\n\nWeinstein has published over 300 articles in peer reviewed scientific and pathology journals, 57 book chapters, and 11 books.  These have been cited over 11,000 times in the science literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ronald_Weinstein2|title=Ronald S Weinstein {{!}} The University of Arizona (UA) {{!}} ResearchGate|website=ResearchGate|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\nWeinstein is president emeritus of the American Telemedicine Association.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2013, he was inducted into the United States Distance Learning Association \"Hall-of-Fame\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usdla.org/awards/hall-of-fame/|title=Hall of Fame|website=www.usdla.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>  The T-Health Amphitheater, in Phoenix, AZ, a \"Classroom-of-the-Future\" co-designed by Weinstein, received the 21st Century Achievement Award, Education and Academia category, from the International Computer World Honors program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cwhonors.org/archives/2008/index.htm|title=Computerworld Honors Program - 2008 Awards Ceremony|website=cwhonors.org|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Involvement in business==\nIn 1982, Weinstein, and his sister and business partner, Beth Newburger, co-founded OWLCAT, Inc., an early entrant in the IBM computer-based, [[S.A.T.]] examination preparation course business.  Two years later, OWLCAT, Inc. was acquired by [[Digital Research Inc.|Digital Research, Inc.]] (DRI).  DRI successfully marketed the OWLCAT education software products.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Pq3POofPsBEC&pg=PA321&lpg=PA321&dq=OWLCAT+Digital+Research+Inc#v=onepage&q=OWLCAT%20Digital%20Research%20Inc&f=false|title=PC Mag|last=Inc|first=Ziff Davis|date=1984-09-18|publisher=Ziff Davis, Inc.|isbn=|location=|pages=321|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Weinstein and Newburger co-founded Corabi International Telemetrics, Inc.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-04-19/business/8701300232_1_chicago-technology-park-research-center-west-side/2|title=Dry Spell Is Ending For High-tech Oasis|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2018-01-17|language=en}}</ref>  Corabi equipped several [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|US Department of Veterans Affairs]] Medical Centers with robotic telepathology systems.  These were used for [[Proof of concept|proof-of-concept]] studies validating telepathology for clinical use.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dunn|first=Bruce E|last2=Almagro|first2=Urias A|last3=Choi|first3=Hongyung|last4=Sheth|first4=Neela K|last5=Arnold|first5=James S|last6=Recla|first6=Daniel L|last7=Krupinski|first7=Elizabeth A|last8=Graham|first8=Anna R|last9=Weinstein|first9=Ronald S|title=Dynamic-robotic telepathology: Department of veterans affairs feasibility study|journal=Human Pathology|volume=28|issue=1|pages=8\u201312|doi=10.1016/s0046-8177(97)90271-9|pmid=9013824|year=1997}}</ref> In 2001, Weinstein co-founded DMetrix, Inc., a [[University spin-off|spin-out]] company of The University of Arizona's [[University of Arizona College of Optical Sciences|College of Optical Sciences]].  DMetrix, Inc. was awarded 29 US Patents on its DX-40 ultra-rapid array microscope digital slide scanner.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cucoranu|first=IoanC.|last2=Pantanowitz|first2=Liron|last3=Parwani|first3=AnilV.|last4=Vepa|first4=Suryanarayana|last5=Weinstein|first5=RonaldS.|date=2014-01-01|title=Digital pathology: A systematic evaluation of the patent landscape|journal=Journal of Pathology Informatics|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=16|doi=10.4103/2153-3539.133112|pmid=25057430|pmc=4060404}}</ref>\n\nFor his work in university technology transfer, he received the University of Arizona's \"2012 Technology Innovator-of-the-Year\" Award.<ref name=\"Beal\">{{cite web|last1=Beal|first1=Tom|title=UA honors innovators for ideas to save lives|url=http://tucson.com/business/local/ua-honors-innovators-for-ideas-to-save-lives/article_c3047d4a-d392-54d9-84f2-09a91e13a949.html|website=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=March 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1964, Weinstein married the former Mary Corabi; they met while they were both working at Woods Hole. They have two grown children and two grandsons.<ref name=\"Visionary\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://alphaomegaalpha.org/leaders.html Weinstein's 1982 interview of Benjamin Castleman] archived in the [[United States National Library of Medicine|National Library of Medicine]]'s \u201c[[Alpha Omega Alpha|AOA Leaders in Medicine]]\u201d video series\n* [https://swtrc.wistia.com/medias/9pmhcqdg3l Weinstein's lecture at the \u201cFred and Janet Sanfilippo Distinguished Leadership\u201d event.] at [[Johns Hopkins Medical School]] describing his work on improving [[health literacy]] for K-12 students\n* [https://isupweb.org/isup/ International Society for Urological Pathology]\n* [http://www.telemedicine.arizona.edu/ Arizona Telemedicine Program]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinstein, Ronald}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:American pathologists]]\n[[Category:Rush Medical College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:Union College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment of telepathology and telemedicine:Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_S._Weinstein"}
