, brain size, and the national IQ of peoples around 3000 years B.C |journal=Personality and Individual Differences |volume=48 |issue=2 |pages=104\u2013106 |doi=10.1016/j.paid.2009.08.020 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Wicherts, Dolan, Carlson, & van der Maas 2010-->\n*{{Cite journal |last=Wicherts |first=Jelte M. |last2=Dolan |first2=Conor V. |last3=Carlson |first3=Jerry S. |last4=van der Maas |first4=Han L.J. |date=June 2010 |title=Raven's test performance of sub-Saharan Africans: Average performance, psychometric properties, and the Flynn Effect |journal=Learning and Individual Differences |volume=20 |issue=3 |pages=135\u2013151 |doi=10.1016/j.lindif.2009.12.001 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Wicherts, Dolan & van der Maas 2010-->\n*{{Cite journal |last=Wicherts |first=Jelte M. |last2=Dolan |first2=Conor V. |last3=van der Maas |first3=Han L.J. |date=January 2010 |title=A systematic literature review of the average IQ of sub-Saharan Africans |journal=Intelligence |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201320 |doi=10.1016/j.intell.2009.05.002 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Witelson, Beresh & Kigar 2006 -->\n*{{Cite journal |last=Witelson |first=S. F. |last2=Beresh |first2=H. |last3=Kigar |first3=D. L. |date=February 2006 |title=Intelligence and brain size in 100 postmortem brains: sex, lateralization and age factors |journal=Brain |volume=129 |issue=2 |pages=386\u2013398 |doi=10.1093/brain/awh696 |pmid=16339797 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Wooldridge 1995-->\n*{{Cite book |last=Wooldridge |first=Adrian |title=Measuring the Mind: Education and Psychology in England c. 1860-c. 1990 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-521-39515-1 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Wroe 2008-->\n*{{Cite book |last=Wroe |first=Andrew |title=The Republican Party and Immigration Politics: from Proposition 187 to George W. Bush |publisher=Macmillan |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-230-60053-9 |page=294 |ref=harv}}\n<!--Zinkstok et al.  2007-->\n*{{Cite journal |last=Zinkstok |first=Janneke R |last2=De Wilde |first2=Odette |last3=Van Amelsvoort |first3=Therese AMJ |last4=Tanck |first4=Michael W |last5=Baas |first5=Frank |last6=Linszen |first6=Don H |year=2007 |title=Association between the DTNBP1 gene and intelligence: a case-control study in young patients with schizophrenia and related disorders and unaffected siblings |journal=Behavioral and Brain Functions |volume=3 |page=19 |doi=10.1186/1744-9081-3-19 |pmc=1864987 |pmid=17445278 |ref={{harvid|Zinkstok et al.|2007}}}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.udel.edu/educ/gottfredson/30years/ June 2005 issue of ''Psychology, Public Policy and Law''], containing papers arguing various perspectives about race and intelligence.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110610230454/http://www.aei.org/event/1425 Debate between James Flynn and Charles Murray] about whether the black/white IQ gap is shrinking or staying the same&nbsp;\u2013 November 2006.\n\n{{Human intelligence topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Race And Intelligence}}\n[[Category:Race (human categorization)|Intelligence]]\n[[Category:Factors related to intelligence]]\n[[Category:Race and intelligence controversy| ]]\n[[Category:Human population genetics]]\n[[Category:Scientific controversies]]\n[[Category:Anthropology]]\n[[Category:Scientific racism|Intelligence]]\n[[Category:Eugenics]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Race_and_intelligence"}
{"title_page": "Uwe Nepp", "text_new": "{{short description|German cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Uwe Nepp\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1966|12|1|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Krefeld]], West Germany\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = \n}}\n\n'''Uwe Nepp''' (born 1 December 1966) is a German former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|team pursuit event]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ne/uwe-nepp-1.html |title=Uwe Nepp Olympic Results |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> Two years later, Nepp placed 21st at the 1990 [[Tour of Belgium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Uwe Nepp|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=117246&season=1990|website=PCS|publisher=PCS|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nepp, Uwe}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of West Germany]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Krefeld]]\n{{Germany-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Uwe Nepp\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| fullname      = \n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1966|12|1|df=yes}} \n| birth_place   = [[Krefeld]], West Germany\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    =\n| role          =\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     =\n| proteam1      =\n| majorwins     =\n| updated       = \n}}\n\n'''Uwe Nepp''' (born 1 December 1966) is a German former [[Cycle sport|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|team pursuit event]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ne/uwe-nepp-1.html |title=Uwe Nepp Olympic Results |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> Two years later, Nepp placed 21st at the 1990 [[Tour of Belgium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Uwe Nepp|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=117246&season=1990|website=PCS|publisher=PCS|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nepp, Uwe}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of West Germany]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Krefeld]]\n{{Germany-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uwe_Nepp"}
{"title_page": "Danfoss", "text_new": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Danfoss A/S\n| logo = Danfoss.svg\n| type = [[private company|Private]]\n| industry = Fluid control equipment, pump, seal, valve manufacturing, climate & energy\n| foundation = [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]]\n| location_city = Nordborg\n| key_people = Kim Fausing, CEO; [[J\u00f8rgen Mads Clausen|J\u00f8rgen M. Clausen]]\n| products = [[Refrigeration]], [[air conditioning]], the control of electric motors, the heating of buildings, solutions for [[renewable energy]] such as [[solar power]] and [[heat pump]]s\n| num_employees = 28,000 (2019)\n| location_country = Denmark\n| homepage = [http://www.danfoss.com/ Danfoss.com]\n}}\n\n'''Danfoss''' is a multinational company, based in [[Denmark]], with more than 28,000 employees globally. Danfoss was founded in 1933 by engineer [[Mads Clausen]].<ref name = \"StoreDanske\">{{cite web |title=Danfoss |url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Erhverv,_karriere_og_ledelse/Erhvervsliv/Erhvervsvirksomheder/Danfoss |website=denstoredanske.dk |publisher=[[Gyldendal]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913002922/http://denstoredanske.dk/Erhverv,_karriere_og_ledelse/Erhvervsliv/Erhvervsvirksomheder/Danfoss |archivedate=13 Sep 2019 |language=Danish}}</ref> \n[[Image:Danfoss Hauptgeb\u00e4ude in Nordborg.jpg|thumb|250px|Danfoss headquarters in [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]].]]\n[[Image:Termostat - Fabrikken 002.jpg|thumb|250px|Cutaway model of Danfoss's first automatic valve]]\n\n== Company history ==\n=== The beginning ===\nIn 1933 [[Mads Clausen]] (1905-1966) founded ''Dansk K\u00f8leautomatik- og Apparatfabrik'', later in 1946 the company name was changed to ''Danfoss''. The first product was an [[Thermal expansion valve|expansion valve]] for refrigeration units, it was developed after studying imported valves from USA.<ref name = \"StoreDanske\"/><br>\nIn 1941 the activities are expanded to products for heating.<ref name = \"StoreDanske\"/> The [[thermostatic radiator valve]] was invented by Mads Clausen in 1943, later patented, and in 1952 promoted as an energy saving device.<ref name=\"JV1\">{{cite web |title=Ikonisk Danfoss-opfindelse fyldte 75 \u00e5r|author1=Claus M\u00f8ller Jensen |url=https://jv.dk/artikel/ikonisk-danfoss-opfindelse-fyldte-75-%C3%A5r |website=jv.dk |publisher=[[JydskeVestkysten]] |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122031/https://jv.dk/artikel/ikonisk-danfoss-opfindelse-fyldte-75-%C3%A5r |archivedate=20 March 2020 |language=Danish}}</ref><br>\nIn 1962 the company started production of [[power electronics]], the first product was custom built [[rectifier]]s, later in 1968 production of the VLT [[Frequency converter]] began, the first of its kind in the world.<ref name=\"Ing1\">{{cite web |author1=Niels Chr. Larsen |title=S\u00e5dan gjorde Danfoss frekvensomformere til et guld\u00e6g |url=https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-gjorde-danfoss-frekvensomformere-til-et-guldaeg-170811 |website=ing.dk |publisher=[[Ingeni\u00f8ren]] |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004182935/https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-gjorde-danfoss-frekvensomformere-til-et-guldaeg-170811 |archivedate=4 Oct 2014 |language=Danish |date=12 Sep 2014}}</ref><br>\nThe company also expands it's activities into [[hydraulics]], the first hydraulic component is produced on the factory in [[Nordborg]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nordic Capitalisms and Globalization |url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=w7QVDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&lpg=PA102&dq=danfoss+hydraulik+1964&source=bl&ots=FAkUb3zov6&sig=ACfU3U0qey8ujdfRtSHP50hOjU989GZm3A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiylvXYzKjoAhWy0KYKHSG6DRAQ6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=danfoss%20hydraulik%201964&f=false |website=Google books |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMads Clausen dies in 1966, only 60 years old. The sons are still too young to take over the company, so Bitten Clausen takes on the role as head of the board. At that times the company had yearly sales of 500 million Danish kroner, and the factory had grown to 10.000 m2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tidsskrift for Ingeni\u00f8r- og Bygningsv\u00e6sen |url=https://www.e-pages.dk/ingarkiv/6241/?page=31&query=mads%20clausen |publisher=ing.dk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131057/https://www.e-pages.dk/ingarkiv/6241/?page=31&query=mads%20clausen |archivedate=20 March 2020 |language=Danish |date=2 Sep 1966}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mads Clausen kontor.jpg|thumb|The office of Mads Clausen as he left it in 1962]]\n\n=== Expansion to the world ===\nExpansion into other countries started in 1956, when the company started to build a factory in [[Flensburg]] in [[Germany]]. The factory was complete in 1958.<ref name=\"Google\">{{cite web |title=Bitten Clausen - historier fra et liv |url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=34kH_vmveCUC&pg=PA105&lpg=PA105&dq=danfoss+f%C3%B8rste+fabrik+i+tyskland&source=bl&ots=J6yjOon28o&sig=ACfU3U3-KGJjlIe0yRnA0GJSqXvm3RQGFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi4wJCNiqvoAhXrtYsKHV4ECGE4HhDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=danfoss%20f%C3%B8rste%20fabrik%20i%20tyskland&f=false |website=Google books |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nChina is also an important market for Danfoss. In 2013 two new factories were opened on the same day, bringing the number up to seven. At that time the Chinese market was the third biggest for the company.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Bent H\u00f8jgaard S\u00f8rensen |title=Danfoss buldrer frem i Kina |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/virksomheder/danfoss-buldrer-frem-i-kina |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321103100/https://www.berlingske.dk/virksomheder/danfoss-buldrer-frem-i-kina |archivedate=21 March 2020 |language=Danish |date=6 Nov 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n''The Danfoss Group'' manufactures products and provides services used in:\n* cooling food \n* [[air conditioning]]\n* heating buildings\n* [[variable-frequency drive]]s\n* [[gas compressor]]s\n* powering mobile machinery. \nDanfoss employs approximately 28,000 people worldwide with its headquarters in [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]].<br>\nIn 2002 Danfoss joined the [[United Nations Global Compact]], consisting of nine principles with social and environmental responsibility.\n\n==Ownership==\n''Bitten og Mads Clausens Fond'' was established as a self-governing institution in 1971 by [[Bitten Clausen]].<ref name=\"Berlingske\">{{cite web |title=Bitten Clausen fylder 100 \u00e5r |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/karriere/bitten-clausen-fylder-100-aar |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317154637/https://www.berlingske.dk/karriere/bitten-clausen-fylder-100-aar |archivedate=19 Mar 2020 |language=Danish}}</ref> Today, the foundation is the biggest shareholder in the company.\n\n==Executive leadership==\n*[[Kim Fausing]], president and chief executive officer\n*Jesper V. Christensen, executive vice president and chief financial officer\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*https://www.danfoss.com/en/about-danfoss/company/financials/year-in-review/\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Danfoss}}\n\n* [http://www.danfoss.com/ Danfoss Group website]\n\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Denmark}}\n\n[[Category:Pump manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Companies based in S\u00f8nderborg Municipality]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Danish brands]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1933]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company \n| name = Danfoss A/S\n| logo = Danfoss.svg\n| type = [[private company|Private]]\n| industry = Fluid control equipment, pump, seal, valve manufacturing, climate & energy\n| foundation = [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]]\n| location_city = Nordborg\n| key_people = Kim Fausing, CEO; [[J\u00f8rgen Mads Clausen|J\u00f8rgen M. Clausen]]\n| products = [[Refrigeration]], [[air conditioning]], the control of electric motors, the heating of buildings, solutions for [[renewable energy]] such as [[solar power]] and [[heat pump]]s\n| num_employees = 28,000 (2019)\n| location_country = Denmark\n| homepage = [http://www.danfoss.com/ Danfoss.com]\n}}\n\n'''Danfoss''' is a multinational company, based in [[Denmark]], with more than 28,000 employees globally. Danfoss was founded in 1933 by engineer [[Mads Clausen]]<ref name = \"StoreDanske\">{{cite web |title=Danfoss |url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Erhverv,_karriere_og_ledelse/Erhvervsliv/Erhvervsvirksomheder/Danfoss |website=denstoredanske.dk |publisher=[[Gyldendal]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913002922/http://denstoredanske.dk/Erhverv,_karriere_og_ledelse/Erhvervsliv/Erhvervsvirksomheder/Danfoss |archivedate=13 Sep 2019 |language=Danish}}</ref>. \n[[Image:Danfoss Hauptgeb\u00e4ude in Nordborg.jpg|thumb|250px|Danfoss headquarters in [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]].]]\n[[Image:Termostat - Fabrikken 002.jpg|thumb|250px|Cutaway model of Danfoss's first automatic valve]]\n\n<br />\n\n== Company history ==\n=== The beginning ===\nIn 1933 [[Mads Clausen]] (1905-1966) founded ''Dansk K\u00f8leautomatik- og Apparatfabrik'', later in 1946 the company name was changed to ''Danfoss''. The first product was an [[Thermal_expansion_valve|expansion valve]] for refrigeration units, it was developed after studying imported valves from USA.<ref name = \"StoreDanske\"/><br>\nIn 1941 the activities are expanded to products for heating.<ref name = \"StoreDanske\"/>The [[thermostatic radiator valve]] was invented by Mads Clausen in 1943, later patented, and in 1952 promoted as an energy saving device.<ref name=\"JV1\">{{cite web |title=Ikonisk Danfoss-opfindelse fyldte 75 \u00e5r|author1=Claus M\u00f8ller Jensen |url=https://jv.dk/artikel/ikonisk-danfoss-opfindelse-fyldte-75-%C3%A5r |website=jv.dk |publisher=[[JydskeVestkysten]] |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320122031/https://jv.dk/artikel/ikonisk-danfoss-opfindelse-fyldte-75-%C3%A5r |archivedate=20 March 2020 |language=Danish}}</ref><br>\nIn 1962 the company started production of [[power electronics]], the first product was custom built [[Rectifier|rectifiers]], later in 1968 production of the VLT [[Frequency converter]] began, the first of it's kind in the world.<ref name=\"Ing1\">{{cite web |author1=Niels Chr. Larsen |title=S\u00e5dan gjorde Danfoss frekvensomformere til et guld\u00e6g |url=https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-gjorde-danfoss-frekvensomformere-til-et-guldaeg-170811 |website=ing.dk |publisher=[[Ingeni\u00f8ren]] |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004182935/https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-gjorde-danfoss-frekvensomformere-til-et-guldaeg-170811 |archivedate=4 Oct 2014 |language=Danish |date=12 Sep 2014}}</ref><br>\nThe company also expands it's activities into [[hydraulics]], the first hydraulic component is produced on the factory in [[Nordborg]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nordic Capitalisms and Globalization |url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=w7QVDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&lpg=PA102&dq=danfoss+hydraulik+1964&source=bl&ots=FAkUb3zov6&sig=ACfU3U0qey8ujdfRtSHP50hOjU989GZm3A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiylvXYzKjoAhWy0KYKHSG6DRAQ6AEwA3oECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=danfoss%20hydraulik%201964&f=false |website=Google books |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMads Clausen dies in 1966, only 60 years old. The sons are still too young to take over the company, so Bitten Clausen takes on the role as head of the board. At that times the company had yearly sales of 500 million Danish kroner, and the factory had grown to 10.000 m2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tidsskrift for Ingeni\u00f8r- og Bygningsv\u00e6sen |url=https://www.e-pages.dk/ingarkiv/6241/?page=31&query=mads%20clausen |publisher=ing.dk |accessdate=20 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320131057/https://www.e-pages.dk/ingarkiv/6241/?page=31&query=mads%20clausen |archivedate=20 March 2020 |language=Danish |date=2 Sep 1966}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:Mads Clausen kontor.jpg|thumb|The office of Mads Clausen as he left it in 1962]]\n\n=== Expansion to the world ===\nExpansion into other countries started in 1956, when the company started to build a factory in [[Flensburg]] in [[Germany]]. The factory was complete in 1958.<ref name=\"Google\">{{cite web |title=Bitten Clausen - historier fra et liv |url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=34kH_vmveCUC&pg=PA105&lpg=PA105&dq=danfoss+f%C3%B8rste+fabrik+i+tyskland&source=bl&ots=J6yjOon28o&sig=ACfU3U3-KGJjlIe0yRnA0GJSqXvm3RQGFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi4wJCNiqvoAhXrtYsKHV4ECGE4HhDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=danfoss%20f%C3%B8rste%20fabrik%20i%20tyskland&f=false |website=Google books |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nChina is also an important market for Danfoss. In 2013 two new factories were opened on the same day, bringing the number up to seven. At that time the Chinese market was the third biggest for the company.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Bent H\u00f8jgaard S\u00f8rensen |title=Danfoss buldrer frem i Kina |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/virksomheder/danfoss-buldrer-frem-i-kina |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=21 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321103100/https://www.berlingske.dk/virksomheder/danfoss-buldrer-frem-i-kina |archivedate=21 March 2020 |language=Danish |date=6 Nov 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n''The Danfoss Group'' manufactures products and provides services used in:\n* cooling food \n* [[air conditioning]]\n* heating buildings\n* [[variable-frequency drive]]s\n* [[gas compressor]]s\n* powering mobile machinery. \nDanfoss employs approximately 28,000 people worldwide with its headquarters in [[Nordborg]], [[Denmark]].<br>\nIn 2002 Danfoss joined the [[United Nations Global Compact]], consisting of nine principles with social and environmental responsibility.\n\n==Ownership==\n''Bitten og Mads Clausens Fond'' was established as a self-governing institution in 1971 by [[Bitten Clausen]].<ref name=\"Berlingske\">{{cite web |title=Bitten Clausen fylder 100 \u00e5r |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/karriere/bitten-clausen-fylder-100-aar |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317154637/https://www.berlingske.dk/karriere/bitten-clausen-fylder-100-aar |archivedate=19 Mar 2020 |language=Danish}}</ref> Today, the foundation is the biggest shareholder in the company.\n\n\n==Executive leadership==\n*[[Kim Fausing]], president and chief executive officer\n*Jesper V. Christensen, executive vice president and chief financial officer\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*https://www.danfoss.com/en/about-danfoss/company/financials/year-in-review/\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Danfoss}}\n\n* [http://www.danfoss.com/ Danfoss Group website]\n\n\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Denmark}}\n\n[[Category:Pump manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Companies based in S\u00f8nderborg Municipality]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Danish brands]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1933]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danfoss"}
{"title_page": "Human Sexuality (book)", "text_new": "{{short description|2003 book by Simon LeVay}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = Human Sexuality\n| image = Human Sexuality cover first edition.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| authors = [[Simon LeVay]]<br>Sharon Valente\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Human sexuality]]\n| publisher = [[W. H. Freeman and Company]]\n| pub_date = 2003\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages =  xviii + 628\n| isbn = 978-0878935703\n| oclc = 61881148\n}}\n'''''Human Sexuality''''' is a textbook about [[human sexuality]] by the neuroscientist [[Simon LeVay]] and Sharon Valente. The book received positive reviews, praising it as a well written book that covered multiple topics and issues related to sex.\n\n==Summary==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\nLeVay discusses human sexuality. Subject addressed include [[sexual orientation]], [[homosexuality]], [[prostitution]], and [[pornography]]. He also discusses related topics such as [[gender]].{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|pages=5, 10, 187\u2013214, 453\u2013489, 617\u2013619, 637\u2013641}}\n\n==Publication history==\n{{more citations|section|date=April 2019}}\nThe book was first published in 2003 by [[W. H. Freeman and Company]]. Subsequent editions have been published by [[Sinauer Associates]], with the second edition appearing in 2006, the third in 2009,{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|page=iv}} and the fourth in 2012. Starting with the third edition, Valente was replaced as a co-author by the sociologist Janice Baldwin.{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|pages=iv\u2013v}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe first edition of ''Human Sexuality'' received positive reviews from William Byne in ''[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]'' and the neuroscientist [[Marc Breedlove]] in the ''[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]]''.{{sfn|Byne|2003|pages=962\u2013963}}{{sfn|Breedlove|2004|pages=169\u2013170}} The second edition received positive reviews from Byne in ''JAMA'' and Sari M. van Anders in the ''Archives of Sexual Behavior'',{{sfn|Byne|2006|page=2539}}{{sfn|Anders|2008|pages=349\u2013351}} and the third and fourth editions received positive reviews from Sigmund Hough in ''Sexuality and Disability''.{{sfn|Hough|2009|pages=179\u2013180}}{{sfn|Hough|2012|pages=375\u2013376}}\n\nByne described the first edition as \"an exceptional preclinical primer that addresses nearly every aspect of sexuality from multiple theoretical, historical, and cultural perspectives\" and suggested that it would \"be an outstanding supplement to medical school and residency courses in sexuality.\" He wrote that it \"provides both information and a model for thinking critically about the complex issues raised in the study of human sexuality.\" He praised LeVay's treatment of gender, and commended his neutrality in dealing with controversial subjects such as pornography and prostitution.{{sfn|Byne|2003|pages=962\u2013963}} Breedlove described the first edition as comprehensive, clearly written, well informed, and free of factual errors. He credited LeVay and Valente with discussing sex in a way that was \"explicit without being judgmental\", and with covering a wide range of topics. He also praised the art included in the book.{{sfn|Breedlove|2004|pages=169\u2013170}} Byne called the second edition \"exceptional\" and credited its authors with assessing \"nearly every aspect of sexuality from multiple theoretical, historical, and cultural perspectives.\"{{sfn|Byne|2006|page=2539}}\n\nAnders described the second edition as clearly written and full of \"interesting facts and commentary\". She considered it \"exceptionally current, with up-to-date examples and content that will be relevant to students and instructors\". She complimented its discussions of topics such as sexual anatomy, sexual differentiation, sexual behavior, and sexually transmitted diseases, though she noted that some topics were excluded and questioned some of the claims made. She concluded that despite these \"caveats or quibbles\", the book was an \"extremely informative and engaging textbook\".{{sfn|Anders|2008|pages=349\u2013351}} Hough called the third edition an \"excellent college and introductory graduate textbook\". He credited LeVay and Baldwin with covering many topics, and praised the illustrations included with their text, and the online resources associated with it.{{sfn|Hough|2009|pages=179\u2013180}} He also praised the fourth edition.{{sfn|Hough|2012|pages=375\u2013376}}\n\nIn ''Evolution and Human Sexual Behavior'' (2013), the anthropologist Peter B. Gray and Justin R. Garcia praised ''Human Sexuality'', describing it as enjoyable to read.{{sfn|Gray|Garcia|2013|page=xiv}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Gray|first1=Peter B. |last2=Garcia|first2=Justin R. |title=Evolution and Human Sexual Behavior |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts and London, England |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-674-07273-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=LeVay|first1=Simon |last2=Baldwin|first2=Janice |title=Human Sexuality, Third Edition |publisher=[[Sinauer Associates|Sinauer Associates, Inc.]] |location=Sunderland |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-87893-424-9 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Human Sexuality (Second Edition) |last1=Anders|first1=Sari M. van |journal=[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]] |volume=37 |issue=2 |year=2008 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Book Review: Human Sexuality. By Simon LeVay and Sharon M. Valente. Sinauer Associates, Sunderland, Massachusetts, 2003, 628 pp., $88.95 |last1=Breedlove|first1=Stephen Marc |journal=[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]] |volume=33 |issue=2 |year=2004 |doi=10.1023/B:ASEB.0000014608.44458.c3 |ref=harv |pages=169\u2013170}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Human Sexuality |last1=Byne|first1=William |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=295 |issue=21 |year=2006 |doi=10.1001/jama.295.21.2539-a |ref=harv |page=2539}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Sexuality Human Sexuality |last1=Byne|first1=William |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=290 |issue=7 |year=2003 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Simon LeVay and Janice Baldwin: Human Sexuality, Third Edition |last1=Hough|first1=Sigmund |journal=Sexuality and Disability |volume=27 |issue=3 |year=2009 |doi=10.1007/s11195-009-9128-x |ref=harv |pages=179\u2013180}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Simon LeVay and Janice Baldwin: Human Sexuality |last1=Hough|first1=Sigmund |journal=Sexuality and Disability |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2012 |doi=10.1007/s11195-011-9256-y |ref=harv |pages=375\u2013376}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human Sexuality (book)}}\n[[Category:2003 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books by Simon LeVay]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Macmillan Publishers books]]\n[[Category:Psychology textbooks]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2003 book by Simon LeVay}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name = Human Sexuality\n| image = Human Sexuality cover first edition.jpg\n| caption = Cover of the first edition\n| authors = [[Simon LeVay]]<br>Sharon Valente\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = [[Human sexuality]]\n| publisher = [[W. H. Freeman and Company]]\n| pub_date = 2003\n| media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]])\n| pages =  xviii + 628\n| isbn = 978-0878935703\n| oclc = 61881148\n}}\n'''''Human Sexuality''''' is a textbook about [[human sexuality]] by the neuroscientist [[Simon LeVay]] and Sharon Valente. The book received positive reviews, praising it as a well written book that covered multiple topics and issues related to sex.\n\n==Summary==\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}}\nLeVay discusses human sexuality. Subject addressed include [[sexual orientation]], [[homosexuality]], [[prostitution]], and [[pornography]]. He also discusses related topics such as [[gender]].{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|pages=5, 10, 187\u2013214, 453\u2013489, 617\u2013619, 637\u2013641}}\n\n==Publication history==\n{{more citations|section|date=April 2019}}\nThe book was first published in 2003 by [[W. H. Freeman and Company]]. Subsequent editions have been published by [[Sinauer Associates]], with the second edition appearing in 2006, the third in 2009,{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|page=iv}} and the fourth in 2012. Starting with the third edition, Valente was replaced as a co-author by the sociologist Janice Baldwin.{{sfn|LeVay|Baldwin|2009|pages=iv\u2013v}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe first edition of ''Human Sexuality'' received positive reviews from William Byne in ''[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]'' and the neuroscientist [[Marc Breedlove]] in the ''[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]]''.{{sfn|Byne|2003|pages=962\u2013963}}{{sfn|Breedlove|2004|pages=169\u2013170}} The second edition received positive reviews from Byne in ''JAMA'' and Sari M. van Anders in the ''Archives of Sexual Behavior'',{{sfn|Byne|2006|page=2539}}{{sfn|Anders|2008|pages=349\u2013351}} and the third and fourth editions received positive reviews from Sigmund Hough in ''Sexuality and Disability''.{{sfn|Hough|2009|pages=179\u2013180}}{{sfn|Hough|2012|pages=375\u2013376}}\n\nByne described the first edition as \"an exceptional preclinical primer that addresses nearly every aspect of sexuality from multiple theoretical, historical, and cultural perspectives\" and suggested that it would \"be an outstanding supplement to medical school and residency courses in sexuality.\" He wrote that it \"provides both information and a model for thinking critically about the complex issues raised in the study of human sexuality.\" He praised LeVay's treatment of gender, and commended his neutrality in dealing with controversial subjects such as pornography and prostitution.{{sfn|Byne|2003|pages=962\u2013963}} Breedlove described the first edition as comprehensive, clearly written, well informed, and free of factual errors. He credited LeVay and Valente with discussing sex in a way that was \"explicit without being judgmental\", and with covering a wide range of topics. He also praised the art included in the book.{{sfn|Breedlove|2004|pages=169\u2013170}} Byne called the second edition \"exceptional\" and credited its authors with assessing \"nearly every aspect of sexuality from multiple theoretical, historical, and cultural perspectives.\"{{sfn|Byne|2006|page=2539}}\n\nAnders described the second edition as clearly written and full of \"interesting facts and commentary\". She considered it \"exceptionally current, with up-to-date examples and content that will be relevant to students and instructors\". She complimented its discussions of topics such as sexual anatomy, sexual differentiation, sexual behavior, and sexually transmitted diseases, though she noted that some topics were excluded and questioned some of the claims made. She concluded that despite these \"caveats or quibbles\", the book was an \"extremely informative and engaging textbook\".{{sfn|Anders|2008|pages=349\u2013351}} Hough called the third edition an \"excellent college and introductory graduate textbook\". He credited LeVay and Baldwin with covering many topics, and praised the illustrations included with their text, and the online resources associated with it.{{sfn|Hough|2009|pages=179\u2013180}} He also praised the fourth edition.{{sfn|Hough|2012|pages=375\u2013376}}\n\nIn ''Evolution and Human Sexual Behavior'' (2013), the anthropologist Peter B. Gray and Justin R. Garcia praised ''Human Sexuality'', describing it as enjoyable to read.{{sfn|Gray|Garcia|2013|page=xiv}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n;Books\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Gray|first1=Peter B. |last2=Garcia|first2=Justin R. |title=Evolution and Human Sexual Behavior |publisher=[[Harvard University Press]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts and London, England |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-674-07273-2 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=LeVay|first1=Simon |last2=Baldwin|first2=Janice |title=Human Sexuality, Third Edition |publisher=[[Sinauer Associates|Sinauer Associates, Inc.]] |location=Sunderland |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-87893-424-9 |oclc= |doi= |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Journals\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Human Sexuality (Second Edition) |last1=Anders|first1=Sari M. van |journal=[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]] |volume=37 |issue=2 |year=2008 |doi= |ref=harv}} {{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Book Review: Human Sexuality. By Simon LeVay and Sharon M. Valente. Sinauer Associates, Sunderland, Massachusetts, 2003, 628 pp., $88.95 |last1=Breedlove|first1=Stephen Marc |journal=[[Archives of Sexual Behavior]] |volume=33 |issue=2 |year=2004 |doi=10.1023/B:ASEB.0000014608.44458.c3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Human Sexuality |last1=Byne|first1=William |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=295 |issue=21 |year=2006 |doi=10.1001/jama.295.21.2539-a |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Sexuality Human Sexuality |last1=Byne|first1=William |journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] |volume=290 |issue=7 |year=2003 |doi= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Simon LeVay and Janice Baldwin: Human Sexuality, Third Edition |last1=Hough|first1=Sigmund |journal=Sexuality and Disability |volume=27 |issue=3 |year=2009 |doi=10.1007/s11195-009-9128-x |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Simon LeVay and Janice Baldwin: Human Sexuality |last1=Hough|first1=Sigmund |journal=Sexuality and Disability |volume=30 |issue=3 |year=2012 |doi=10.1007/s11195-011-9256-y |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human Sexuality (book)}}\n[[Category:2003 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books by Simon LeVay]]\n[[Category:English-language books]]\n[[Category:Macmillan Publishers books]]\n[[Category:Psychology textbooks]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Sexuality_(book)"}
